<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deliberates Louima Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A jury deliberated for six hours without  
reaching a verdict in the case of four officers accused of helping 
a fellow officer sodomize a handcuffed Haitian immigrant with a 
broom stick. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury was due back Monday in a case that shocked the city for  
its alleged brutality and raised tensions between police and 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The case had five defendants, but one, Officer Justin Volpe,  
pleaded guilty midway through the trial of committing the actual 
assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the four remaining defendants, one officer is accused of  
holding Abner Louima down in a stationhouse bathroom; two are 
accused of beating him in a police car on the way to the 
stationhouse and the fifth is charged with helping cover up the 
crime. 
</P>
<P>
	While Louima identified Volpe in court, he could only identify  
the second officer as the driver of the patrol car that brought him 
to the stationhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe assaulted Louima because mistakenly thought Louima had  
punched him in a melee outside a nightclub. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 04:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army Pilot Pleads Guilty in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT STEWART, Ga. (AP) -- One of two pilots blamed for a  
helicopter crash last summer in the Bahamas that killed their wives 
has admitted he did not have the authority to allow the women on 
the aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Warrant Officer Daniel Riddell, who was in control of the  
UH-60 Black Hawk helicopter when it crashed, told a military judge 
Friday that he was guilty of wrongful violation of a military order 
for permitting the women on the maintenance test flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell told the judge that he and Chief Warrant Officer David  
Guido were only authorized by their commander to take the 
helicopter on the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all we were briefed for and we did allow the wives on  
board the aircraft,'' Riddell said. 
</P>
<P>
	The July 6 crash near Grand Exuma Island airport killed Rebecca  
Riddell and Pam Guido. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell also pleaded guilty Friday to willful dereliction of  
duty. The combined charges carry a maximum of two years in prison, 
dismissal from the Army and forfeiture of military pay and 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wanted to simply accept responsibility for what he did,  
which was allow the wives to have the helicopter ride they 
wanted,'' said Riddell's attorney, Doug Andrews. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell still faces charges of conspiracy, misappropriation of a  
military aircraft, making a false official statement and conduct 
unbecoming an officer. His court-martial is scheduled for June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido's court-martial is to begin next week. He faces similar  
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	During a hearing held in March to determine whether the men  
would go to trial, one investigator testified the accident was 
caused by a ``pitch-back attack,'' a maneuver that causes the 
helicopter to abruptly change directions by spinning the tail. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers have said a mechanical failure was to blame and  
that the pilots did nothing dangerous. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
