<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 21:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	N. Albania Shelled by Serbs  
</P>
<P>
	TIRANA, Albania (AP) -- Yugoslav forces shelled a northern  
Albanian border town crowded with refugees late Saturday, 
international officials said. One person died and several were 
injured in the shelling, which targeted an Albanian army barracks 
about five miles west of the border, according to Andrea Angeli, a 
spokesman for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe. Angeli also said three shells hit the nearby village of 
Nikoliq, injuring three women. In the border areas, rebels from the 
Kosovo Liberation Army are still trying to move fighters and 
supplies into the province to further their fight for independence. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia: Peace Signing Near  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- A Kosovo peace agreement might be signed  
Sunday, Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency reported, quoting 
unnamed sources. NATO sources said the agreement would contain 
specific conditions for withdrawal, but refused to detail them. 
When the alliance verifies that the conditions have been met, NATO 
air attacks on Yugoslavia will be suspended and allied peacekeeping 
troops will begin entering Kosovo, the sources said on condition of 
anonymity. No timetable was given, however. NATO also will keep 
open the option of resuming bombing until the withdrawal is 
complete, the sources said. 

</P>
<P>
	Shuttle Plans Night Landing  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The space shuttle Discovery was  
scheduled to touch down on Kennedy Space Center's floodlighted 
runway early Sunday in a rare night landing. But Mission Control 
informed the seven astronauts there was a chance that rain and wind 
could keep them up an extra day. The astronauts accomplished their 
last orbital job -- releasing Starshine, a glittery, educational 
satellite. Commander Kent Rominger and his crew spent six of their 
10 days in orbit at the new unmanned international space station, 
dropping off supplies and making repairs. 

</P>
<P>
	Singer Mel Torme Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jazz and pop singer Mel Torme, known as ``the  
Velvet Fog,'' died early Saturday. He was 73. Torme, died of 
complications from a 1996 stroke after being rushed from his 
Beverly Hills home to a hospital, his publicist said. ``He was one 
of the supreme jazz singers of all time,'' said singer Jack Jones 
of Torme. 

</P>
<P>
	Crashed Jetliner Is Dismantled  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- American Airlines crews began  
dismantling the shell of a jetliner Saturday while mourners 
attended the first of several memorial services for the nine people 
killed in the crash of Flight 1420. Federal investigators hope to 
learn more about the mechanics of the plane's spoilers -- wing 
panels used to slow an airplane after landing. Although the 
co-pilot has said he believes the captain set the spoilers, a 
flight data recorder indicates they never popped up when the plane 
landed in a severe thunderstorm Tuesday and skidded off the end of 
the runway. 

</P>
<P>
	D-Day Re-Enacted in Normandy  
</P>
<P>
	COLLEVILLE-SUR-MER, France (AP) -- On the eve of the 55th  
anniversary of D-Day, June 6, 1944, U.S. troops re-enacted the 
World War II landing Saturday in France. The memorial was staged by 
active duty soldiers on Omaha Beach. Also Saturday, paratroopers of 
the 82nd Airborne Division jumped over the La Fiere Bridge, and 
officials later laid wreaths and held a service at the American 
Cemetery. Thousands of veterans from several nations were on hand 
for this weekend's commemorations. 

</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid Wins Belmont Stakes  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lemon Drop Kid won the Belmont Stakes Saturday  
and denied the Triple Crown to Charismatic, who finished third and 
pulled up hurt. Another longshot, Vison and Verse, was second. 
Charismatic, the Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner, fractured two 
bones in his left front leg. ``That means he's through as a 
racehorse,'' said Dr. Larry Bramlage. ``We expect him to be fine as 
a stallion.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Jones Becomes Undisputed Champion  
</P>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- Roy Jones unified the light heavyweight  
boxing title Saturday night by winning every round in a brutal 
beating of Reggie Johnson. Jones, who said Johnson was partially 
responsible for his split with his father, punished the Houston 
fighter from the third round on, punching him at will in the late 
rounds. Jones, 40-1 with 33 knockouts, became the first undisputed 
light heavyweight champion since Michael Spinks relinquished the 
title in 1985 to campaign as a heavyweight. Jones won 120-106 on 
the three judges' cards. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Beat Pacers  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With 5.7 seconds left, Larry Johnson made a  
four-point play to give the New York Knicks a 92-91 win Saturday 
night over the Indiana Pacers in Game 3 of the NBA Eastern 
Conference finals. New York trailed 91-88 when Johnson took an 
inbounds pass and he was fouled while making a 3-point shot. 
Johnson made the decisive free-throw. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
