<DOCNO> APW19990605.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 06:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UPI Suspends Spanish Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- United Press International is suspending its  
Spanish language service at the end of June as part of a 
restructuring plan, the company's chief executive said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnaud de Borchgrave said the move was part of a restructuring  
plan he announced in January when he took the news service's top 
job after decades of magazine and newspaper work. He said Thursday 
that the goal of those changes is to move UPI away from ``hourly 
news leads'' and toward developing an investigative wire, programs 
based on the Web and links to research centers and think tanks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The suspension of the Spanish service ... enables us to get  
away from the humdrum routine news coverage,'' de Borchgrave said. 
</P>
<P>
	UPI plans to re-enter the Spanish-language market with new  
products next year, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 08:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> South Dakota Tornado Kills One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PIERRE, S.D. (AP) -- The tiny town of Oglala on the Pine Ridge  
Indian Reservation was hit by a tornado Friday night, and one 
person is dead and several are reported injured. 
</P>
<P>
	National Weather Service spotters reported at least three  
tornadoes near Pine Ridge, and severe storms were reported in other 
parts of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	A 46-year-old man was killed. Six people were missing, including  
a baby living in with the man. 
</P>
<P>
	John Mousseau of the Pine Ridge Police Department said early  
Saturday that many homes were hit by a tornado at Oglala. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe 20 mobile homes were destroyed and 50 other residences  
were damaged,'' he told The Associated Press. ``The tornado hit 
right into a housing cluster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rescue workers from several counties were called to Oglala,  
Mousseau said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the homeless spent the night in dormitories at the Pine  
Ridge High School, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Highway Patrol has set up an emergency command center at  
Oglala, and Sgt. Larry Weelborg said the National Guard also is 
helping out. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bill Janklow was on his way to Oglala, according to Pine  
Ridge Police. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three people were taken to a Rapid City hospital with  
head injuries, and there's an unconfirmed report of at least one 
death, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been pretty hectic,'' Weelborg said. ``Some trailer  
houses were totally wiped out, and other houses had their roofs 
torn off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanie Jealous, a dispatcher for the Pine Ridge Police  
Department, said her office had received reports of people getting 
trapped under trailers. 
</P>
<P>
	The electricity went out when the storm hit, so tracking the  
storm was difficult, Jealous said. 
</P>
<P>
	A flash flood warning was in effect for southern Jackson County  
because of heavy rain. In some areas, the storm dumped between 2 to 
3 inches of rain in an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	One-inch hail pelted parts of Bon Homme, Charles Mix and Gregory  
counties. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind gusts up to 70 mph were clocked near Oelrichs, in Fall  
River County, and along the South Dakota-Nebraska border. 
</P>
<P>
	Oelrichs Fire Chief Larry Forney said the first report of a  
tornado came at about 5:45 p.m. when the storm was spotted 8 miles 
south of Oelrichs. 
</P>
<P>
	High winds and hail the size of grapefruits hit ranches in the  
area as the storm moved northeast toward Oglala. 
</P>
<P>
	Forney said the violent storm crossed mostly open prairie, and  
he had no reports of major property damage until the tornado hit 
Oglala. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
