<DOCNO> APW19990605.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 11:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Aims for Late-Night Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery's astronauts  
accomplished their last orbital job Saturday -- releasing Starshine, 
a glittery, educational satellite -- then aimed for a rare 
middle-of-the-night landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery was scheduled to touch down on Kennedy Space Center's  
floodlighted runway early Sunday. Mission Control informed the 
seven astronauts there was a chance that rain and wind could keep 
them up an extra day. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA's space shuttles have landed in darkness only 10 times  
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Commander Kent Rominger and his crew spent six of their 10 days  
in orbit at the new international space station. They left 2 tons 
of tools, water, clothes and other supplies for the first permanent 
crew, due to arrive next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Before departing Thursday, the astronauts also fixed a broken  
radio, replaced flawed battery packs, and made it quieter by 
installing mufflers over noisy fans. 
</P>
<P>
	This was only the second crew to visit the orbiting outpost. The  
first crew connected the station's two components in December. And 
it will be this December before shuttle astronauts arrive with more 
supplies. First, the Russians must launch their long-delayed 
service module; that's scheduled for November. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery's astronauts briefly set aside their packing for  
Saturday morning's release of Starshine, a 19-inch sphere covered 
with 878 small, circular mirrors that were polished by 
schoolchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	It's purely an educational project; more than 25,000 students  
around the world will track the sparkling satellite over the next 
seven to eight months and, in doing so, determine the density of 
the atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	Reminiscent of a 1970s disco ball, the $1 million Starshine  
twinkled as it popped out of a canister in the shuttle cargo bay 
and floated away. It quickly was spotted by observers on the ground 
with the naked eye. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a fantastic sight,'' said Canadian astronaut Julie  
Payette, who pushed the ejection button. ``The first thing we all 
saw was the flickering of the mirrors ... We could track it with 
our cameras for the longest time because it's now and then getting 
a flash. It's beautiful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The project's director, Gil Moore of Utah State University, said  
the satellite should remain in orbit until January before it 
plunges through the atmosphere and burns up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We invite everybody in the world to track this thing,'' Moore  
said. ``This is not just for kids. It's for students of all ages.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 00:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co-Pilot Says Approach Was Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Despite gusting winds, the descent of  
American Airlines Flight 1420 seemed fine until it touched down on 
a wet runway and couldn't stop, the co-pilot told federal 
investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	The MD-82 jet skidded off the runway at about 90 mph, hitting a  
bank of lights and steel walkway before breaking apart and bursting 
into flames Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight passengers and the pilot died.  
</P>
<P>
	At a hospital room Friday where he is recovering from injuries,  
First Officer Michael Origel told investigators that he believed 
the pilot took the necessary steps to safely land the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Origel described the flight and descent into Little Rock  
National Airport as being ``normal,'' said George Black Jr., a 
member of the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	But after touchdown, ``the first officer felt that they  
hydroplaned down the runway, and the reason for that is he did not 
feel the normal decelerating forces that would be expected,'' Black 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators have been especially curious about the plane's  
wing panels -- or spoilers -- which are supposed to pop up at 
touchdown to help slow the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	A flight data recorder, which monitored at least two of the  
panels, showed they never opened. 
</P>
<P>
	But Origel said he noted on an American Airlines-mandated  
checklist that Capt. Richard Buschmann had set the spoilers to 
deploy, Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He believed that the captain did arm the spoilers,'' Black  
said while summarizing the two-hour interview. ``Our people did not 
feel that he was being deceptive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flight data recorders also indicated the jet's thrust reversers  
-- used to slow the plane -- were turned on and off. The thrust 
reversers usually remain engaged until the plane slows to a speed 
at which the pilot can safely steer it on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Origel said he saw the captain activate the thrusters, shut them  
off, then activate them again. Because the engines on an MD-82 are 
close to the fuselage, engaging the thrusters affects how well the 
pilot can control the rudder, and turning them off gives the pilot 
better control, he told investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said the plane was traveling at 165 mph when it landed  
2,000 feet down the 7,200-foot runway -- about the proper location. 
It slowed only to 90 mph over the next mile of runway, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Black also said that while Origel and some passengers believed  
the jet hydroplaned, a NASA expert on hydroplaning said the jet had 
a good grip on the runway. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm produced wind gusts of 60-75 mph before reaching the  
airport. Investigators are trying to determine how strong the 
crosswinds were as the plane approached. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, several survivors made a tearful return to the scene,  
looking from a rock levee about 100 yards away from the crumpled 
plane as it lay on the banks of a rain-swollen and fast-moving 
Arkansas River. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors and relatives were given red and pink roses as they  
got off the buses. Some laid the flowers on a makeshift memorial 
made of hay bales. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were tears. People as a group kind of consoled each  
other,'' said Jimmy Manus of Benton, whose wife and their two 
daughters were on the plane. ``They were glad they made the trip 
today.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 03:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston's Portugal Won't Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Boston's Mark Portugal is back with the Red Sox  
after flirting with retirement. But he's no longer in the starting 
rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal, who strongly considered ending his career to spend  
more time with his three children, decided Friday to remain with 
the Red Sox. But he has struggled lately and is just 3-3 with a 
5.33 ERA and will be used in relief, manager Jimy Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	That, Portugal said, is fine with him.  
</P>
<P>
	The bigger issue in his life is finding a way to spend more time  
with his children, who live in nearby Barrington, R.I., after his 
marriage of 11 years ended in divorce during last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal, who pitched with Philadelphia the past two seasons,  
signed as a free agent with Boston to be closer to his children -- 
Derek, 10, Jacob, 6, and Alexandra, 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``But with the night games and the road schedule, at times it  
feels like I've been a Saturday afternoon father on homestands,'' 
Portugal said. 
</P>
<P>
	He expects to be able to spend more time with his children once  
the school year ends this month. One reason he decided against 
retirement was their desire to see him play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came back because I love to play baseball and my kids love  
to see me play baseball,'' Portugal said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he didn't make his decision until he arrived in Boston's  
clubhouse before Friday night's 5-1 win over Atlanta and after 
meeting with Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the questions I asked Jimy is if he wants me on his  
team. He said, `most definitely.' That was reassuring,'' Portugal 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Darn right we want him back on this team. He can help us,''  
Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, though, his scheduled start Sunday will be taken by Pat  
Rapp. There's no indication when Portugal, 36, will return to the 
rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he wants to continue playing.  
</P>
<P>
	``This has been my life for the last 18 1/2 years. It's given me  
everything I have,'' he said. ``You don't know how long you'll play 
this game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his last outing, Portugal allowed six runs and lasted three  
innings in Monday's 8-7 win over the Detroit Tigers. He left the 
ballpark in a hurry without talking to reporters. He said his mind 
wasn't in the game and he apologized to teammates and Williams 
about his behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	He was ``angry, upset and confused'' at the time and, after  
talking with his agent, team officials and others since then, 
decided to remain active, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to go home and think about this from a father's  
perspective and from a baseball player's perspective,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal first came to the majors in 1985 with Minnesota and  
played with Houston, San Francisco and Cincinnati before joining 
Philadelphia in 1997. His career record entering this season was 
102-83 with a 3.89 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	He signed a $2.7 million, one-year contract with the Red Sox, a  
deal that gives Boston a $3.3 million option with a $300,000 buyout 
for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have problems and bad days at our job where we just  
want to toss it out the window,'' Portugal said. ``And sometimes we 
don't get a second chance to do what we love to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been rough seas, but we've weathered the storm now.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
