<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres' Rasmussen Proves Himself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Erik Rasmussen knew he could make it in the  
NHL, and he was getting tired of trying to prove it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres kept the bruising young forward shuttling between  
Buffalo and its AHL affiliate in Rochester for most of this past 
winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Check the oil. Fill the tank.  
</P>
<P>
	Rasmussen rubbed his eyes while speeding along one cold night  
outside of Batavia and asked himself: 
</P>
<P>
	``Is this the way I really want to spend my life?''  
</P>
<P>
	The answer came last Monday when Rasmussen beat Toronto's Curtis  
Joseph to send Buffalo to its first Stanley Cup final since before 
he was born. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the 22-year-old Sabres forward is packing summer clothes for  
a trip to Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``A Stanley Cup final,'' he said. ``I don't even know what to  
say. I don't even know how I feel about it. Right now I'm trying to 
concentrate on the next game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the puck drops in Dallas on Tuesday, Rasmussen will try to  
knock the luster off a Dallas Star. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hitting gets me into the game,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter  
whether I'm doing the hitting or being hit. Sometimes when I get 
hit, it wakes me up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-2, 205-pound Minnesotan is one player an opponent  
really ought to let sleep. His hits stirred things up in Buffalo's 
Marine Midland Arena this season. 
</P>
<P>
	First would come the tremendous bang rising above the crowd  
noise. The glass would bend. The crowd would roar. The visiting 
team would sag. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hitting is a big part of his game,'' said Joe Juneau,  
Rasmussen's linemate. ``It gives us a big boost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rasmussen can also score and make plays. H had only three goals  
and seven assists in 42 regular-season games while bouncing back 
and forth between Buffalo and Rochester, but two goals and two 
assists in the playoffs have allowed Rasmussen to finally let the 
lease expire on his Rochester apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	His two playoff assists were on game-winning goals.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's here for good,'' said wing Miroslav Satan, Buffalo's  
leading scorer. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Rasmussen lives with Sabres defenseman Jay McKee, another  
young player who has proved himself this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what it is exactly that's made me stick this  
time,'' Rasmussen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting used to the grind of the pro game has helped. Drafted in  
the first round by Buffalo in 1996, Rasmussen spent most of the 
1997-98 season in Rochester. 
</P>
<P>
	This season he's found consistency as he's gotten used to the  
grind. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem was more mental than physical,'' he said. ``One  
night I would play well and the next night I would disappear. In 
the NHL you can't take a night off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Resentment was Rasmussen's companion on many of those trips to  
Rochester. But he realized that his time in the minors was not a 
demotion after all. It was part of his preparation for a Stanley 
Cup final. 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn a lot in the minors,'' said Rasmussen, who struggled  
during his sophomore season at Minnesota. ``I learned how to score 
again and make plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His goals aren't pretty. The game-winner in Toronto came off a  
brilliant play by linemate Brian Holzinger, whose shot caromed off 
Joseph's stick and straight to Rasmussen, who snapped the tie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not the type of player who's going to skate the length of  
the ice and beat five guys and score a goal,'' Rasmussen said. ``I 
have to settle for the ugly ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To a team that has never won a Stanley Cup since it joined the  
league in 1970 and hasn't played in a Cup final since it lost to 
Philadelphia in 1975, Rasmussen's most recent goal was a thing of 
beauty. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so proud of him scoring that goal,'' Sabres wing Dixon  
Ward said. ``He's made great strides.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
