<DOCNO> APW19990605.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 00:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National League Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Brian Bohanon can't pinpoint why he has stopped  
winning. 
</P>
<P>
	The free-agent acquisition, who heard talk of an All-Star berth  
after beating the Arizona Diamondbacks with a complete-game victory 
on May 14, hasn't won since. 
</P>
<P>
	Bohanon couldn't provide any answers Friday night after going 6  
1-3 innings for the Colorado Rockies and failing for the fourth 
straight time to get his seventh victory, although they rallied to 
win 9-8 in 10 innings over the Milwaukee Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are they looking off-speed late? Are they giving up on my cut  
fastball all together?'' Bohanon asked. ``There are a few different 
scenarios.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bo didn't have his best stuff, but he hung in there and  
pitched like a champ,'' Colorado manager Jim Leyland said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bohanon was long gone before Dante Bichette's RBI single with  
two outs in the 10th inning, his fourth hit of the game, gave 
Colorado the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am getting sick and tired of just going out there and just  
keeping the team in the game,'' Bohanon said. ``These are games 
that should be won, and I'm just not doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Veres (2-2), who blew the save in the ninth, was the winner  
for Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Darryl Hamilton, who reached on a fielder's choice, was at  
second base with two outs when Larry Walker was intentionally 
walked by Bob Wickman (2-3). Bichette, who broke a 2-for-34 slump 
with an RBI double in the fifth, then hit the first pitch to 
left-center field for the game-winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Bichette finished 4-for-6 with three RBIs and two doubles.  
</P>
<P>
	``Coming home helped a lot as well as the fans and being in  
situations that were really motivating helped a lot,'' said 
Bichette, who is hitting .241 with two home runs and 16 RBIs on the 
road, but .313 with six homers and 23 RBIs at home. ``I am more 
relaxed at home, and when you are relaxed, you can be a little 
quicker, think a little better and see the ball a little better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers, who have lost eight of 11, rallied in the ninth to  
tie the game 8-8. Marquis Grissom's two-out single off Veres with 
the bases loaded scored Mark Loretta, but Ron Belliard was thrown 
out at the plate for the third out. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not swinging the bats well,'' Milwaukee manager Phil  
Garner said despite the Brewers' 17-hit attack. ``You are swinging 
the bats when you are driving in runs when you need them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care if we had only gotten three hits. They ought to  
come when we need them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado took an 8-7 lead in the eighth on a two-out RBI single  
by Bichette off David Weathers. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker's 11th homer of the season, a two-run shot in the seventh  
off reliever Al Reyes, gave the Rockies a 6-5 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado's Henry Blanco drove in a run with a career-high three  
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Grissom had four hits and two RBIs for Milwaukee, and Loretta  
and Alex Ochoa each had two hits and an RBI. David Nilsson had a 
solo homer for the Brewers. Starter Jim Abbott went six innings in 
his first career appearance against the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Milwaukee has been in sole possession of last place in the  
NL Central since May 15. ... Catcher Kirt Manwaring rejoined the 
Rockies from Triple-A Colorado Springs, where he played seven games 
on an injury rehabilitation assignment. ... Nilsson has three 
homers in his last two games. ... Milwaukee has scored 73 runs on 
136 hits in its last 12 games. ... Colorado is 3-2 in extra innings 
this year. ... A Milwaukee starter has pitched at least six innings 
in five of the past six games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
