<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 01:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Unionization Vote Unresolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) -- Which union will represent pickers  
and packers at the country's largest strawberry grower remains an 
open question as state labor officials review contested ballots 
that have held up final results of a runoff election. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 1,400 workers at Coastal Berry Co. turned out Thursday  
and Friday to choose between the United Farm Workers and a rival 
union, Coastal Berry of California Farm Worker Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Committee received 688 votes, while the United Farm Workers  
had 598, state labor officials said. No winner could be announced 
because another 92 ballots were contested, preventing either union 
from gaining the required majority. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Agriculture Labor Relations Board will begin  
investigating the contested ballots on Monday, said Freddie 
Capuyan, an agent for the board who is overseeing the election. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Farm Workers union has been trying to unionize  
Coastal Berry for several years in hopes of building momentum for 
union contracts throughout California's $600 million, 20,000-worker 
strawberry industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of the union made famous by Cesar Chavez figured Coastal  
Berry was the best place to start, since owners vowed to be neutral 
towards the unions, a rare move in the anti-union strawberry 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	But the United Farm Workers has struggled to win the confidence  
of workers, and has consistently trailed the upstart Coastal Berry 
of California Farm Worker Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Committee, which has no president and no negotiating  
experience, also got the most votes at the initial election last 
week, but failed to get the required majority, forcing the runoff. 
</P>
<P>
	United Farm Workers spokesman Marc Grossman said the union was  
disappointed in the latest results. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't just up against this Committee, we were really  
against an entire strawberry industry that is rich and powerful and 
greedy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At its most powerful in 1970, United Farm Workers had 80,000  
members. But the figure dwindled to 20,000 by the time Chavez, the 
union's legendary founder, died in 1993. Since then, it has grown 
to 27,000 members. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 17:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
