<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 06:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Cancels More Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A weeklong sickout by pilots forced Cathay  
Pacific Airways to ground half its scheduled flights Friday, but 
airline officials said the situation appears to be improving and 
resumed taking flight bookings for selected routes. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines and the main pilots' union plan to meet Saturday to  
discuss their differences. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay cancelled 59 of the 117 flights scheduled Friday -- the  
highest number yet -- but began accepting bookings for Bangkok, 
Manila, Taipei, Kuala Lumpur, and Singapore ahead of its meeting 
with the pilots' union on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay had to charter 26 flights from other airlines to carry  
the passengers, but Tony Tyler, Cathay's director of corporate 
development, said in a statement that the situation ``was showing 
signs of stabilizing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The airline angered the pilots by demanding pay cuts averaging 8  
percent in exchange for stock options, and the situation 
deteriorated last week when the company gave the pilots until June 
11 to either take a revised offer -- including a smaller pay cut and 
better stock options -- or lose their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay was forced to cancel many flights since last Friday, when  
pilots began phoning in sick, saying the layoff threats had left 
them too stressed-out to fly. They have threatened a strike vote if 
Cathay starts firing pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	John Findlay, the union's secretary general, would not say  
whether the union would make any concessions at Saturday's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can say is we're walking in tomorrow with an open mind  
and see where we go from there. Tomorrow is the start of a possible 
resolution of this issue,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Thursday, Hong Kong's labor officials successfully  
persuaded Cathay management to reopen talks with the leaders of the 
Hong Kong Association of Aircrew Officers, the main pilots's union. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay had said earlier it would not back down unless the pilots  
withdraw demands for annual pay increases if they take two years of 
cuts and a yearlong pay freeze. 
</P>
<P>
	Katherine Wang, a Cathay spokeswoman, insisted Friday that  
management has ``no intention to change any elements of our pay 
proposals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay lost $69 million last year, running up its first loss  
since 1963 as passenger traffic plunged amid Asia's economic 
crisis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 15:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Angels' Park Ejected After Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Chan Ho Park was  
ejected from Saturday's game against the Anaheim Angels after 
throwing a forearm and a kick at Anaheim pitcher Tim Belcher. 
</P>
<P>
	The altercation unfolded after Park's sacrifice bunt with one  
out in the fifth in a game the Angels led 4-0 thanks to Matt 
Walbeck's grand slam an inning earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Belcher fielded Park's bunt and tagged him out. After a brief  
exchange of words, Park forearmed Belcher in the face and followed 
that up with a kick-boxing move that connected before Belcher 
wrestled him to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Both benches and bullpens emptied, but there were no further  
incidents and the game was held up for only about five minutes. 
Park was ejected after the umpires conferred briefly. 
</P>
<P>
	Belcher, apparently uninjured, retired Eric Young on a fly to  
center to end the inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the game, Park had knocked down Randy Velarde twice  
with pitches near his head. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Park was involved in an altercation with Tony  
Phillips during an Angels-Dodgers game in Anaheim after hitting 
Phillips with a pitch. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
