<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 15:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SLOC Targets T-Shirt Vendor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A federal judge has ordered a Park City  
retailer to stop selling bootleg Olympic T-shirts. 
</P>
<P>
	Charging trademark infringement, the Salt Lake Organizing  
Committee and the U.S. Olympic Committee sued the Park City Shirt 
Company and got a restraining order Friday from U.S. District Court 
Judge Tena Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trying to beat up anybody and we didn't ask for any  
money,'' said Mark Lewis, SLOC's vice president of marketing and 
licensing. ``We just asked that they turn the product over and take 
it off the shelves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Company owner Paula Henry said he complied with the court order  
after making about 100 of the T-shirts, which carried the words 
``2002 Winter Games'' and ``Winter Olympics, Park City USA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic officials vigorously protect the ``Olympic'' trademark  
and have taken action before against unlicensed merchandise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wasatch Brew Pub, also in Park City, ran into trouble when  
it dubbed one of its ales the ``unofficial beer of the 2002 Winter 
Games.'' Threatened with a lawsuit, the brewery-restaurant settled 
for a simple ``2002'' and the 'no' symbol -- a red circle and slash. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic movement relies heavily on licensing income from  
Olympic products and legitimate vendors won't pay as much if ``they 
know they're going to be competing with counterfeit products,'' 
Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Winter Games draw nearer, Lewis said, he expected other  
entrepreneurs and ``knock-off artists'' to attempt making money on 
the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we want to do is try to stop it early,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
