<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BYU's Myles-Mills Wins 100M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Leonard Myles-Mills didn't pay any attention  
to the more heralded runners in the men's 100 meters at the NCAA 
Outdoor Track and Field Championships -- and made his own kind of 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	The BYU senior raced to victory Saturday in 9.98 seconds, making  
him the first repeat champion in the event since Auburn's Harvey 
Glance in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Glance, now the coach at Alabama, was on hand to present the  
first-place medal to Myles-Mills. 
</P>
<P>
	The winning time was a record at Boise State's Bronco Stadium  
and tied Mills for eighth place on the all-time collegiate list. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into the race, all of the attention was focused on  
Southeastern Conference champion Coby Miller of Auburn and SEC 
runner-up John Capel of Florida. Neither came close to Myles-Mills 
as Capel was second in 10.03 and Miller sixth in 10.21. 
</P>
<P>
	After 14 of the 21 men's events, Stanford led with 50 points,  
followed by SMU with 29, Southern California with 24 and seven-time 
defending champion Arkansas with 23. 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's standings, defending champion Texas led with 46  
points after 15 events. Southern California was second with 39 and 
UCLA third with 36. 
</P>
<P>
	Suziann Reid helped the Longhorns take the lead by winning the  
400 for the third time in four years in 51.09, a stadium record. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were depending on me to get 10 points,'' Reid said.  
</P>
<P>
	There was a surprise in the women's 100, as Southern California  
freshman Angela Williams, the 1998 High School Athlete of the Year, 
beat two-time defending champion Debbie Ferguson of Georgia. 
Williams bolted into the lead at the start and finished in 11.04. 
Ferguson was second in 11.10. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the greatest day of my life,'' Williams said. ``It's  
like the Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the easiest victory in one of the short races was turned  
in by South Carolina's Terrence Trammell. He won the men's 110 
hurdles in 13.45, a stadium record, and two meters ahead of 
runner-up Dawane Wallace of Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	In a blanket finish, Miami's Yolanda McCray won the women's 100  
hurdles in 12.85 with Georgia Tech's Andria King second in 12.87 
and UCLA's Joanna Hayes third in 12.89. 
</P>
<P>
	Northeast Louisiana's Andras Haklits has to go outside the  
Southland Conference to find hammer-throw competition because the 
event is not part of the league's program. 
</P>
<P>
	Haklits found the opposition to his liking, winning with a heave  
of 243 feet, 1 inch on his final attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first three throws were bad,'' the freshman from Hungary  
said. ``Also, my fourth was very bad. My fifth was better, and on 
my last throw, I just let it go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haklits' big effort enabled him to surpass Norbert Horvath,  
another Hungarian who competes for Southern California, and 
defending champion and two-time NCAA indoor weight-throw champion 
Libor Charfreitag of Slovakia and SMU. Horvath wound up second at 
241-11 and Charfreitag was third at 239-10. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam Connolly of Stanford, the son of 1956 Olympic hammer throw  
champion Harold Connolly, finished fourth at 236-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Hungary is known for its hammer throwers, and has three of the  
world's best. Tibor Gecsek, who coached Haklits before he came to 
the United States, is ranked No. 1. Balazs Kiss, the 1996 Olympic 
gold medalist and four-time NCAA champion for Southern California 
from 1993-96, is No. 2, and Adrian Annus is No. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why Haklits plans to compete for Croatia -- rather than  
Hungary -- in this year's World Championships and next year's 
Olympics. He spends a lot of time in Croatia and has dual 
citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	``Croatia hasn't got any good throwers,'' Haklits, 21, said. ``I  
am the best. In Hungary, I could never make the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haklits came to the United States last August on a scholarship.  
He chose Northeast Louisiana because he knows a member of the 
women's basketball team and her father was his physical education 
teacher in high school in Szombathely, Hungary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here, I get everything free -- a scholarship, meals, a dorm,''  
he said. ``At home, I didn't get anything free. My parents paid for 
everything.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
