<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Knicks-Pacers To Settle It on Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- It's time for the Indiana Pacers and the New  
York Knicks to settle their differences on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	The two clubs have exchanged angry words in the days leading up  
to tonight's Game 3 of the Eastern Conference finals in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	New York coach Jeff Van Gundy complained Thursday about the  
Pacers' play and the officiating. The Pacers responded Friday by 
saying the talk won't change anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just them being what they said we were, a bunch of  
babies, a nursery and whining,'' Mark Jackson said. ``I've been 
beat up for two games. When I missed shots, I simply said I missed 
shots. It didn't make a difference how they were playing me. I 
didn't complain. I'm not going to complain, so don't look for a 
cop-out or bail-out now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy claimed officials are keeping his point guards from  
defending Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers fired off a few shots of their own as they practiced  
Friday at Market Square Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no whining on our part. Everything is coming from  
their camp,'' said Reggie Miller, accused by Van Gundy of taking 
cheap shots at the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy also accused Rik Smits of a cheap shot and said he  
called NBA vice president Rod Thorn about the play in the opening 
two games in the best-of-7 series. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller wasn't concerned.  
</P>
<P>
	``If they're going to call Rod Thorn and beg for calls, they  
need to look at themselves in the mirror. They're the ones that are 
doing all the hitting and the holding,'' Miller said. ``We're just 
trying to play basketball. ... It's too late in the season to be 
crying now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series is tied 1-1 going into tonight's game at Madison  
Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks will be without center Patrick Ewing, gone for the  
rest of the season with a partially torn Achilles' tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana coach Larry Bird said Van Gundy's comments were directed  
at officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's trying to work the officials, which is good. It's all  
part of the game,'' Bird said. ``We say things how we feel. 
Obviously, he's not too happy right now. ... It's up to us to just 
go there and play basketball.'' 
  	   	
