<DOCNO> APW19990605.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 06:00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Makes it Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                      *Asssociated Press Writer    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton made it official  
Friday: She will begin raising money to travel to New York, conduct 
polls and hire staff -- all forming the nucleus of a Senate 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to open an exploratory committee in July. And then  
I'll spend some time -- a lot of time -- in New York listening to 
people and I'm looking forward to that,'' Mrs. Clinton announced 
almost offhandedly at the end of an ABC ``Good Morning America'' 
broadcast on youth violence. 
</P>
<P>
	In political circles, formation of such a committee is  
tantamount to a declaration of candidacy, making Mrs. Clinton the 
nation's first first lady to seek public office for herself. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's running for office. She's running,'' said James  
Carville, the political mastermind of Bill Clinton's 1992 
presidential victory and an informal adviser to Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	At the helm of Mrs. Clinton's political operation, Harold Ickes  
said her decision -- not yet cemented in stone but in a state of 
``high mull'' -- is driven by a commitment to public service and a 
realization that ``in order to be effective in public service, you 
need a platform, a structure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't be sort of a wandering minstrel. She herself likes  
structure,'' Ickes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours of her announcement, a group called Conservatives  
for Effective Leadership alerted reporters that it was creating a 
new political action committee -- complete with direct-mail campaign 
and mass-media advertising -- to oppose any ``Hillary for Senate'' 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Has she ever introduced a piece of legislation, run a business  
or even served on her local school board? The answer is no,'' said 
radio talk show host and CEL president Gary Nolan. ``She is only a 
leader to those liberals that confuse words with action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers to the first lady, a Yale-trained lawyer who led her  
husband's efforts in Arkansas to reform the state's schools and in 
the White House to overhaul health policy, said she is prepared for 
a political brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a race that could pit her against the no-holds-barred  
Republican mayor of New York City, Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody has sugar coated how tough this will be for her,'' said  
media adviser Mandy Grunwald, a veteran of Bill Clinton's 
presidential campaign who is likely to enlist in Mrs. Clinton's 
Senate bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``She knows, she's been told and she's proceeding,'' Grunwald  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The exploratory committee, which can raise money within federal  
contribution limits of $1,000 per individual and $5,000 for a 
political action committee, is meant to quiet a bubbling 
controversy over Mrs. Clinton's testing-the-waters trips through 
New York under the guise of official business on the taxpayers' 
dime. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't need to wander into that thicket,'' said Democratic  
political consultant Jim Duffy, who estimated that Mrs. Clinton 
will need to raise between $20 million and $25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's got to be very careful. They need to raise money and put  
it in the bank so this conflict-of-interest thing doesn't become a 
problem,'' Duffy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's political team plans to be prepared to begin  
collecting money almost as soon as she forms the committee. Ickes 
said her first trip on the committee's tab will come in early July. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fair to say when she establishes the exploratory  
committee she will be in position to ask people almost immediately 
for contributions,'' Ickes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Will Mrs. Clinton be making fund-raising calls herself?  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know yet. That is still very much in flux,'' Ickes  
said. ``Typically what happens in these things is she will contact 
people and ask them for support and have somebody else come in 
behind her and actually ask for the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday night, the Schenectady County Democratic Committee  
became the first county organization in New York to endorse -- by 
unanimous approval of about 100 local party leaders -- the first 
lady as a Senate candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Carville, who met with Mrs. Clinton at the White House earlier  
Thursday, said he will help with her campaign, but said he would 
not have an official staff role. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exploratory committee underway, Mrs. Clinton must next  
``start thinking about a timetable, thinking about people, putting 
a staff together. There's a gazillion things you have to do,'' 
Carville said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pointing up the juggling act Mrs. Clinton will have to master,  
those gazillion things will wait until she completes a 
long-planned, two-week trip later this month through Europe and the 
Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will slow her down a little bit,'' said Grunwald, who  
nonetheless contended it is a political plus for Mrs. Clinton to 
remind New Yorkers now of her international reputation as an 
advocate for women and children. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 02:50:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Writers Clash on Movie Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Jack Valenti, the Washington  
lobbyist for the top Hollywood studios, says filmmakers should do 
more to eliminate gratuitous violence from their pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should look at their creative work and say, `Is this the  
best that I can do? Is there something here that is gratuitous as I 
define it?''' Valenti said Friday during a gathering of 
screenwriters called to debate entertainment violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Valenti -- who has taken much heat from Congress on the issue --  
said he'll fight for the writers' First Amendment rights. But he 
said people in the movie business need to take personal 
responsibility and cut needless violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The event comes as lawmakers go on the attack against movies,  
television, music and video games following the school massacre in 
Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and Congress have taken Hollywood to task,  
suggesting the industry has contributed to a culture of violence 
through the bloody images in the product. 
</P>
<P>
	At a seminar titled ``Guns Don't Kill People ... Writers Do,''  
Brian Helgeland, writer and director of the ultraviolent Mel Gibson 
film ``Payback,'' said writers should answer only to themselves and 
not adhere to a code of conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't know how to respond to a code or a consensus as to  
what's responsible and what isn't acceptable. That is only for me 
to answer in my own work,'' said Helgeland, who also co-wrote 
``L.A. Confidential'' and ``Nightmare on Elm Street 4.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But William Mastrosimone, who wrote the HBO movie ``The Burning  
Season'' and the CBS miniseries ``Sinatra,'' said Helgeland's 
perspective was ``very dangerous'' and ``extremist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to look to ourselves and acknowledge the effect we  
have in the world,'' said Mastrosimone, contending that studies 
clearly show a cause-and-effect relationship between entertainment 
violence and people's real-life behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	At the seminar, Callie Khouri, the Academy Award-winning writer  
of ``Thelma &AMP; Louise,'' which starred Susan Sarandon and Geena 
Davis, said the issues are more complicated than simply blaming one 
segment of society or another for youth violence. 
</P>
<P>
	She noted that she was surprised when audiences applauded a  
scene in her movie in which one character shoots a man. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hoped for a stunned reaction from audiences and realization  
that the character just sealed her fate,'' Khouri said. ``I was 
terrified and I realized that I can't control how my work is 
perceived.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 02:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navajos Fear Drought's Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Every day, Marilyn Watchman leads her family's  
sheep herd through a canyon on the remote Navajo reservation in 
northeastern Arizona, just as generations before her did. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a tradition she fears another summer of drought could steal  
from her family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I might have to sell them all,'' Watchman said of her flock.  
``But then there wouldn't be anything to live for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tribal officials worry the summer may bring a return to harsh  
conditions to the already unforgiving land. In 1996, when the 17 
million-acre reservation saw only an inch of rain, crops dried up 
in summertime and sick, skinny cows died on the desert floor. 
</P>
<P>
	This winter was even drier, and mountain snowpacks are at record  
lows. 
</P>
<P>
	Many who live here are ranchers like Watchman, making their  
living selling the sheep and cattle they tend. Others hold jobs in 
the reservation's small towns but maintain smaller ``hobby herds'' 
at their rural homes, providing a connection to Navajo traditions 
and beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing a disastrous summer, the Navajo government is urging  
older cattle be sold and hobby herds be removed from the land. Next 
week, Navajo Nation president Kelsey Begay plans to use radio 
addresses to ask tribal members to take voluntary safeguards to 
prevent overgazing. 
</P>
<P>
	But choosing between the land and tradition won't be easy, said  
Harry Walters, a professor of Navajo culture at Dine College in 
Tsaile, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	Maintaining a hobby herd is ``not a hobby,'' Walters said.  
``It's a way of life. (Animals) don't really belong to us; they 
belong to the holy people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herds of any size provide Navajos with a vital relationship with  
the land that could vanish along with the animals, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a connection Watchman feels deeply.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I ride along with my cattle, I just feel in harmony with  
the world,'' said Watchman, whose herd already has dwindled to 45 
cattle and sheep, roughly one-third of its former size. ``It's like 
a release.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More worrisome, Watchman said, are thoughts of what her family  
will do if the animals disappear. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of us didn't go after a good education because we were  
planning on taking care of our livestock,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 00:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sabres Know About Stanley Cup Flops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Six Buffalo Sabres know the satisfaction of  
making it to the Stanley Cup finals, and all six know the 
disappointment of losing. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Woolley, Joe Juneau, Stu Barnes, Rhett Warrener, Alexei  
Zhitnik and Dominik Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	Five had the embarrassment of a sweep heaped atop the  
disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolley, Barnes and Warrener played for the Florida Panthers  
when they were swept by Colorado three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts a lot, and I don't want to have that feeling again,''  
said Woolley, Buffalo's leading scorer in the playoffs. 
</P>
