</P>
<P>
	Woolley says there's a lot to handle both on and off the ice.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know exactly what I'm getting into, from the media exposure  
to focusing properly and handling the tickets and handling the 
family,'' he said. ``It's something that our young guys are going 
to have to pick up and learn real fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, maybe the biggest lesson to be learned from a crash  
in the Cup final is to forget it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be thinking about the past,'' Woolley said.  
``I'm not going to be thinking about the last time I was there. I'm 
just going to be going forward and trying to win this thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``You really have to cherish this. It's a very special moment.  
And to win, how cool that would be.'' 
  	   	
</P>
