<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 13:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Leaders Talk Peace  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO officials met all afternoon with  
Yugoslav generals at a Macedonian coffeehouse along the Kosovo 
border today to spell out the exact terms for the withdrawal of 
Serb troops from Kosovo. The talks adjourned after five hours, and 
a NATO spokesman, Lt. Col. Robin Clifford said the Yugoslavs asked 
for more time to consult ``higher authorities'' about terms of the 
withdrawal. Clifford said the meeting will resume tomorrow morning 
at NATO's Kumanovo base in Macedonia. He called the talks ``very 
constructive ... with positive results.'' Nevertheless, the failure 
to reach agreement today casts doubt on whether the air campaign 
will end this weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugees Tell of Beatings  
</P>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- As NATO and Yugoslav generals discussed  
the terms of a withdrawal from Kosovo, more refugees straggled 
across the border into Albania today telling of brutal beatings by 
Serb police. The refugees, 86 men from two villages, crossed into 
Albania after being released from a prison where they had been held 
for four days for alleged links to Kosovo guerrillas. Bedri Selmani 
said he and many of the others were beaten with wooden staves and 
kicked by Serb police as they walked toward Albania. Some of the 
refugees were treated by medical workers for severe bruises. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: End Mental Illness Stigma  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton kicked off a White House  
campaign today designed to erase the stigma of mental illness. ``In 
too many of our hearts,'' he said, ``mental illness is 
misunderstood and feared.'' The president teamed with Tipper Gore 
in his weekly radio address as a prelude to Monday's first White 
House conference on mental illness. ``Too many people with mental 
illness are denied the opportunity to fully participate in American 
life,'' Clinton said. Mrs. Gore disclosed recently that she 
underwent treatment for depression. 

</P>
<P>
	Shuttle Aims for Late-Night Landing  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery's astronauts  
accomplished their last orbital job today -- releasing Starshine, a 
glittery, educational satellite -- then aimed for a rare 
middle-of-the-night landing. Discovery is scheduled to touch down 
on Kennedy Space Center's floodlighted runway early tomorrow. 
Mission Control informed the seven astronauts there is a chance 
that rain and wind could keep them up an extra day. 

</P>
<P>
	India Delays Pakistan Peace Talks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India and Pakistan failed to agree on a  
date for peace talks today for the disputed Kashmir region, where 
ground forces were locked in combat and Indian artillery targeted 
separatist rebels. Pakistan's offer to send Foreign Minister Sartaj 
Aziz to New Delhi on Monday ``is not convenient,'' said Raminder 
Singh Jassal, an Indian foreign ministry spokesman. India would 
soon suggest alternative dates, he said. India and Pakistan have 
fought two wars over the Himalayan province. India controls 
two-thirds of Kashmir, Pakistan the rest, and both claim all of it. 

</P>
<P>
	Singer Mel Torme Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mel Torme, whose warm, smooth vocal delivery  
made him a hero to fellow jazz and pop singers and earned him the 
nickname ``The Velvet Fog,'' died early today at age 73. Torme, who 
had suffered a mild stroke in August 1996, was rushed from his home 
in Beverly Hills to University of California, Los Angeles. He died 
of complications from the stroke at 1:45 a.m., Torme's publicist 
said. Torme was also celebrated as the co-author of the holiday pop 
classic ``The Christmas Song.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Graf Beats Hingis at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Steffi Graf won her sixth French Open title and her  
first Grand Slam championship in almost three years today with a 
come-from-behind victory over top-ranked Martina Hingis. Graf then 
said it was her last appearance at Roland Garros, but she would not 
say if this was her last year on the tour. Hingis served for the 
match at 5-4 in the second set but could not hang on. The women's 
No. 1 received a warning and was penalized a point for several 
outbursts, and was frequently booed by the center court fans. 

</P>
<P>
	Rams Give Top Pick Holt $10M Deal  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Torry Holt gave himself a memorable 23rd  
birthday present today, signing a five-year, $10 million contract 
with the St. Louis Rams. In addition to the money, which includes a 
$5.4 million signing bonus, the Rams threw in a chocolate cake at a 
news conference for their first-round pick. Holt caught 88 passes 
for 1,604 yards and 11 touchdowns his senior season at North 
Carolina State. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
