<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 03:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sick Tarantula Gets Top-Notch Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CATONSVILLE, Md. (AP) -- When tarantula No. 79011 gets angry, she  
rears up, shows her fangs and shoots barbed hairs from her rump. 
It's a good thing she's been a perfect patient so far. 
</P>
<P>
	The Goliath tarantula, the largest spider species in the world,  
underwent a second CAT scan Friday in hopes of saving her from a 
nasty infection oozing from her side. 
</P>
<P>
	Giving a CAT scan to a spider is not a regular event, but this  
spider is worthy of saving, say those who know her. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has a robust, loose personality,'' said Sandy Barnett,  
senior herpetologist at The National Aquarium in Baltimore. ``I 
really hope we can help her out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The prognosis wasn't good. Doctors are planning to perform a  
lifesaving operation next week to try to save the eight-legged 
creature. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 79011, weighing in at a hefty 2 1/2 ounces, is the size of a  
salad plate, has dark brown hair, and a turret of eyes atop a flat 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	She also has an abscess the size of a quarter that is causing  
her to lose fluid. Instead of walking on the tips of her toes like 
a ballerina, she's down at the heel -- a sure sign of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	An antibiotic ointment had no effect and another technique,  
punching a hole in her side to drain the infection, could kill her, 
said Dr. Brent Whitaker, the aquarium's director of animal health 
who is to perform the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	During surgery, the same artificial skin used in human surgery  
will be used to create a covering over the abscess. The abscess can 
then be drained and more artificial skin can be used to seal the 
drain hole, Whitaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Ian Walker, a veterinary intern at the aquarium who hopes to  
assist Whitaker, said his biggest fear is that he could break into 
the body cavity by mistake, causing her powder blue blood to leak 
out uncontrollably. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will probably lose the animal anyway if we don't try,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tarantula, which comes from South American rain forest, is  
worth all the effort, Whitaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't discriminate,'' he said. ``All of our animals get  
top-notch care.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 08:10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. Senator: Save Security Pension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Protecting Social Security surpluses from  
other government functions is key to the retirement program's 
future, a Republican senator said today in his party's weekly radio 
address. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, co-chairman of the Senate  
Republican task force on Social Security, urged Democrats to 
support a GOP effort to legally separate the program's funds from 
the rest of the budget, preventing raids for other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans believe voting to preserve the Social Security  
surplus for Social Security alone is a critical first step to 
preserving Social Security's long-term future,'' Santorum said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can take this step together and begin the important work of  
putting the system on a fiscally sustainable course for the 21st 
century,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 416-12 vote last month, the House passed legislation that  
would make it harder for lawmakers to spend surpluses coming from 
Social Security taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Senate version of the bill faces resistance from  
Democratic leaders. A procedural vote in April fell six votes short 
of the 60 needed to consider the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration opposes the legislation, saying it  
would hinder the government's day-to-day cash flow without actually 
doing anything to help Social Security out of a financial crisis 
looming after baby boomers retire in droves in the 21st century. 
</P>
<P>
	Santorum has proposed letting workers take part of the money  
they now pay in Social Security taxes and invest it in the stock 
market through a personal retirement account, although he did not 
mention this in his address. 
</P>
<P>
	Skepticism has been growing that Congress can pass a full-scale  
overhaul before the 2000 presidential election. The GOP drive to 
formally separate the Social Security surpluses is partly a 
fallback plan to counter Democrats' accusations that Republicans 
want to spend the money on tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Social Security is now collecting more money than it  
pays out, a financing shortfall is expected after baby boomers 
retire and begin to collect benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's federal budget surplus, expected to be $80 billion  
to $110 billion, will come entirely from Social Security taxes. The 
pending legislation would forbid Congress or the president from 
including that and future Social Security-generated surpluses in 
budgeting for other programs or for tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Santorum accused Clinton of raiding Social Security for $53  
billion next year and $158 billion over the next five years for 
other government programs in his fiscal 2000 budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``When one considers that the system is already in fiscal  
jeopardy, spending this money only aggravates the problem,'' 
Santorum said in his speech, recorded Friday in Pittsburgh. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 10:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pantani Barred From Tour of Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADONNA DI CAMPIGLIO, Italy (AP) -- Marco Pantani was barred from  
the Tour of Italy Saturday, two stages from his second consecutive 
triumph, after tests showed unusually high levels of red blood 
cells. 
</P>
<P>
	The high counts can signal the use of the banned growth hormone  
EPO, but also can occur naturally. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian television quoted the team as saying dehydration and the  
high altitude of Friday's leg of the race might be responsible for 
Pantani's reading. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani, leaving his hotel two hours after the 21st stage of the  
Giro had started without him, said he could not understand what had 
happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry for cycling ... but there is something strange in  
this affair,'' the 29-year-old Italian said, saying a blood test 
Friday night showed no irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	``This morning, I had a bitter surprise,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Italy's Tg2 quoted him, off-camera, as saying he might retire.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have restarted after serious accidents ... but this time my  
morale has really hit the bottom,'' Pantani said when asked about 
the question of retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	International Cycling Union doctors performed the tests on  
Pantani and other cyclists hours before the start of the 21st stage 
of the cycling marathon. The top 15 competitors in overall 
standings were reportedly tested. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani's count was red blood cell count 52, Italian media said.  
The UIC maximum is 50. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Pantani was prevented from starting in the leg and  
barred from competing for 15 days, organizers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the law. We had to stop him,'' Hein Verbruggen, head of  
the UIC, told Italy's ANSA news agency. ``It's a hard blow for 
cycling because the No. 1 has been hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All competitors had been tested before the start of the race in  
Agrigento, Sicily, last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Two unheralded cyclists, Nicola Loda and Javier Ochoa Palacios,  
were stopped by UIC doctors then because of high red blood cells 
count. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani, one of the best world climbers, had virtually clinched  
the Tour of Italy on Friday by winning his fourth stage at this 
resort in the Dolomite mountains, extending his lead by more than 5 
1-2 minutes over the closest rival, Paolo Savoldelli. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's stage started without the pink jersey since  
Salvodelli, the new leader, refused to wear it. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the events of Saturday ``the worst thing that could  
have happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Savoldelli now holds a 34-second lead over compatriot Ivan  
Gotti, the 1997 Giro winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani had won both the Giro and the Tour of France last year --  
the latter rocked by a doping scandal that took the prestigious 
French race to the brink of suspension. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 10:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
