<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Commanders Meet  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO and Yugoslav generals met for five  
hours in a coffeehouse on the Macedonia-Yugoslavia border today to 
work out exact terms of a Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo -- a key 
condition for the allied bombings of Yugoslavia to halt. Alliance 
jets, meanwhile, struck in Belgrade, Kosovo's capital of Pristina 
and at military targets just 12 miles from the talks even as 
British commander Michael Jackson was joined at the Europe cafe by 
a delegation of Yugoslav generals. After the Serbs headed back by 
car to Yugoslav territory, a NATO spokesman said they needed to 
confer with Yugoslav authorities on ``a few points of detail'' in 
the withdrawal plan. 

</P>
<P>
	Singer Mel Torme Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mel Torme, whose warm, smooth vocal delivery  
made him a hero to fellow jazz and pop singers and earned him the 
nickname ``The Velvet Fog,'' died early today at age 73. Torme, who 
had suffered a mild stroke in August 1996, was rushed from his home 
in Beverly Hills to University of California, Los Angeles at 1 a.m. 
He died of complications from the stroke at 1:45 a.m., Torme's 
publicist said. His wife Ali and five children were at his side 
when he died, Wilcox said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: End Mental Illness Stigma  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton kicked off a White House  
campaign today designed to erase the stigma of mental illness. ``In 
too many of our hearts,'' he said, ``mental illness is 
misunderstood and feared.'' The president teamed with Tipper Gore 
in his weekly radio address as a prelude to Monday's first White 
House conference on mental illness. He said the session will seek 
ways to dispel myths about the mentally ill. ``Too many people with 
mental illness are denied the opportunity to fully participate in 
American life,'' Clinton said. Mrs. Gore disclosed recently that 
she underwent treatment for depression. 

</P>
<P>
	New S. Africa Leader Mulls Cabinet  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- As President-elect Thabo Mbeki  
pondered his Cabinet choices today, reports emerged that more than 
a quarter-million people not on voter lists cast ballots in last 
week's elections. With Mbeki's African National Congress on the 
verge of winning a two-thirds majority -- which would allow it to 
change the constitution -- the issue is critical, New National Party 
spokeswoman Juli Kilian said. With results in from all polling 
stations, the ANC had 66.2 percent of the vote. Final official 
results aren't expected until tomorrow. Eight opposition parties 
have hired an independent auditor to verify the results. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Returns to Poland  
</P>
<P>
	GDANSK, Poland (AP) -- Welcomed as Poland's favorite son, Pope  
John Paul II returned to his homeland today and paid tribute to the 
Baltic port city of Gdansk where the ``cry of conscience'' against 
communist rule rang out. Tens of thousands of Poles lined streets 
and highways to get a glimpse of the frail, 79-year-old pope at the 
start of his 13-day tour. John Paul's first visit to Poland as pope 
20 years ago helped spark the creation of Solidarity, the first 
free labor union in the Soviet bloc. Formed a year after the visit, 
Solidarity spread into a nationwide movement that toppled communism 
in 1989. 

</P>
<P>
	Graf Beats Hingis at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Steffi Graf won her sixth French Open title and her  
first Grand Slam championship in almost three years today with a 
come-from-behind victory over top-ranked Martina Hingis. Graf, 
cheered on by the fans at Roland Garros, fought back to beat Hingis 
4-6, 7-5, 6-2 in a turbulent match on a cloudy day in Paris. Hingis 
served for the match at 5-4 in the second set but could not hang 
on. Hingis, who lost her second French Open final in three year, 
received a warning and was penalized a point for several outbursts, 
and was frequently booed by the center court fans. 

</P>
<P>
	Wizards Eye Isiah Thomas As Coach  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Detroit Pistons star and Toronto  
Raptors general manager Isiah Thomas appears to be the leading 
candidate for the Washington Wizards head coaching position. 
Thomas, now a commentator on NBC's NBA broadcasts, has been 
involved in talks with Wizards owner Abe Pollin about the opening, 
according to today's edition of the Washington Post. The 
38-year-old led the Pistons to NBA championships in 1989 and 1990. 
He was GM of the Raptors from 1994-97. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
