<HEADLINE> Rivers Is Frontrunner for Magic Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Orlando Magic officially remained  
without a coach Saturday, although the search to fill the vacancy 
appeared to be over. 
</P>
<P>
	Doc Rivers, who played 13 NBA seasons before retiring three  
years ago, has been the leading candidate to succeed Chuck Daly for 
two weeks and reportedly is ready to sign a four-year guaranteed 
contract worth about $8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone messages left by The Associated Press at Rivers' home  
in San Antonio were not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Magic officials also did not return calls, although club  
spokesman Joel Glass said Friday night that an announcement was not 
expected over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orlando Sentinel reported that Rivers, 37, would become the  
league's second-youngest coach behind New York's Jeff Van Gundy on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Magic brought Rivers to town for an interview last Wednesday  
and he remained for a second day of talks that clearly established 
him as the frontrunner for the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Orlando player and current Phoenix Suns assistant Scott  
Skiles interviewed the day before Rivers. The team has not 
scheduled talks with any other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers, who has been working as a television analyst for Turner  
Sports, has said he was impressed with the Magic front office as 
well as the commitment to win in Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly retired May 24 with one year left on a contract worth $5  
million per season, leaving behind a team that overachieved during 
the regular season only to lose to Philadelphia in the first round 
of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Rivers has no prior coaching experience, he played much  
of his career for Mike Fratello in Atlanta and Pat Riley in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sentinel said three former NBA coaches -- Dave Wohl, Jim  
Cleamons and Johnny Davis -- are under consideration to be Rivers' 
top assistant. As many as two of Daly's assistants, including 
Brendan Suhr, could be retained as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The Magic reportedly have been interested in Rivers ever since  
he retired as a player in 1996 and targeted him as Daly's successor 
several days before the Hall of Fame coach announced his 
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly, 68, left broadcasting to re-enter coaching in 1997 but had  
an option after the second season of his three-year deal to 
continue coaching for $5 million, accept a consultant's position at 
$200,000 or leave for another team. 
</P>
<P>
	The new coach is expected to join general manager John Gabriel  
and the rest of the Orlando staff in Chicago for the start of the 
NBA pre-draft camp on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
