<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 00:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks' Williams Might See Time  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Herb Williams, the oldest player in the NBA,  
might see something other than garbage time in Game 3 of the 
Eastern Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old Williams could be called into service if the  
Knicks' big men get into foul trouble tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to be able to play a normal rotation,' coach Jeff Van  
Gundy said Friday. ``Whether that happens or not, you've got to be 
prepared for everything. I don't want Herb to have to play 25 
minutes because of foul trouble early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who spent the first 7 1/2 years of his career with  
Indiana and is the franchise's 10th-leading career scorer, is the 
Knicks' only true backup center now that Patrick Ewing is hurt and 
Chris Dudley is moving into the starting lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Still a popular player in Indianapolis, Williams nonetheless  
says he has no lingering affection for the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Me and some of their players get along real well, but we're  
trying to get a championship here,'' Williams said. ``It's not 
about being fond of the team. I'm fond of the Knicks, that's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 3 of the series, tied 1-1, tips off about 6:40 p.m. EDT.  
Game 4 is Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know they've been a much better road team in the playoffs  
than they have at home. They were up 30-27 (after one quarter) at 
Milwaukee, 28-22 at Philly and 31-17 at Philly, and we have to be 
ready. No one plays better on the road,'' Van Gundy said. 
</P>
<P>
	After wavering Thursday, Van Gundy on Friday announced his  
decision to go with Dudley. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, this is the simplest,'' Van Gundy said. ``You can get  
guys in as early as you want, you can change early if that's what 
you need to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley started 16 games during the regular season, four  
alongside Ewing and 12 when Ewing was out with Achilles' 
tendinitis. In the 12 games without Ewing, the Knicks went 7-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Patrick's been out in the past, that's how we've been,''  
Van Gundy said. ``We've had some good wins, some tough losses. 
We'll start the same, and everyone will stay in their same 
pattern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That means Latrell Sprewell, the team's leading scorer, will  
continue to play as a reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks used their third straight day of rest to go over what  
they need to do now that they don't have Ewing. Doctors discovered 
a slight tear in Ewing's Achilles' tendon on Wednesday and declared 
him out for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Allan Houston, Sprewell, Larry Johnson and the two point guards,  
Charlie Ward and Chris Childs, will need to contribute more 
offensively. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like Patrick was averaging 20 shots a game,'' Houston  
said. ``We had a lot of balance before Patrick went out, so it's 
going to change, but it's not going to change to the point where 
certain people are going to take 10 or 20 more shots per game and 
overextend themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tonight's game will only be the third for Indiana in two weeks  
since it completed a sweep of Philadelphia in the semifinals May 
23. For the Knicks, it will be their third in 12 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's been great for us,'' coach Larry Bird said of the  
extensive practice time his team has had. ``We got a lot of things 
accomplished. We put in some new stuff on the offensive end. We've 
had time to prepare, and that should help us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks are expecting to see improved offensive production  
from Rik Smits now that his chances of getting into foul trouble 
while guarding Ewing have been reduced. Van Gundy would not say 
whether Dudley would start with the defensive assignment on Smits, 
or whether he will continue handing that task to Kurt Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy also warned that the Knicks cannot overlook Dale and  
Antonio Davis, both of whom have hurt the Knicks offensively. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you go into the game trying to avoid foul trouble, you  
can't be effective. We've got to be aggressive, tenacious and 
passionate, but we also have to be smart,'' Van Gundy said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
