<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules Against AT&AMP;T </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- A federal judge dealt a blow to AT&AMP;T Corp.  
on Friday, ruling that the telecommunications company must allow 
rival Internet companies in the Portland area access to its 
high-speed cable lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The case could set a nationwide precedent, allowing other local  
authorities to require similar conditions. AT&AMP;T plans to appeal the 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T brought the lawsuit in January after months of haggling  
about open Internet access with the city of Portland, Multnomah 
County and eight local cable regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very straightforward matter,'' said City Commissioner  
Erik Sten. ``We want people to have choice. We're the only city 
that held firm and kept the requirement in place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case stems from AT&AMP;T's recent $48 billion acquisition of  
Tele-Communications Inc. Before AT&AMP;T could take over TCI's network 
of high-speed, broadband cables, the company needed to obtain 
approval from thousands of local regulators across the country who 
determine cable franchise rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of communities have approved those transfers, but  
Portland area cable officials said they would only approve the 
transfer if AT&AMP;T guaranteed that competing Internet-service 
providers had access to the lines as well. Anything less would 
stifle competition, local officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T balked and took them to court.  
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, U.S. District Court Judge Owen Panner ruled that the  
``open access'' condition was within the rights of the local 
authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Local franchising authorities have the power to determine  
whether a change of ownership or control would 'eliminate or reduce 
competition,' '' Panner wrote. ``It is not my role to second-guess 
the findings supporting the decision to impose open access.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Rosenblum, vice president for legal affairs and federal  
regulation for AT&AMP;T, said AT&AMP;T's merger does not restrict access to 
the Internet because most people log on through regular phone 
lines, not the broadband cable under consideration. Among the 
high-speed phone lines, wireless connections and satellite links, 
there is more than enough competition for Internet access, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenblum noted that only about 100,000 people nationwide  
currently gain access to the Internet through broadband cable. 
</P>
<P>
	Other cities, such as Los Angeles, Denver and Dallas, are still  
grappling with the issue of whether to renew AT&AMP;T's franchise 
rights in their areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington, D.C.-based OpenNet Coalition, a group of more  
than 70 Internet service providers, hailed the ruling, calling a 
victory for the right of local communities to require competition 
in the Internet marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Thurburn, chairman of FlashNet Communications, a member of  
OpenNet, hoped Friday's decision will inspire them to regulate 
high-speed cable hookups as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``The city of Portland has been very brave in taking on AT&AMP;T in  
the battle,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of America Online, also one of the coalition's members,  
rose $12 to $117.75 on the New York Stock Exchange on news of the 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, AT&AMP;T slipped 87 1/2 cents to $53.37 1/2, while At Home  
Corp., which has access to AT&AMP;T's cable properties, dropped $10.75 
to $94.50, also on the NYSE. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
