<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> One American in Impressionists Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mary Cassatt was the lone American among the  
French Impressionists -- a largely male, Parisian bunch -- and the 
most important work she did in the United States disappeared nearly 
a century ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But her art has grown in popularity in recent years, with one  
painting selling for more than $4 million in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting Sunday, a major show at the National Gallery of Art  
will feature 55 of her paintings and drawings. All that remains of 
her major U.S. project, though, are small black and white photos of 
the 14-by-58-foot mural painted for Chicago's Columbian Exposition 
of 1893. 
</P>
<P>
	Known chiefly as a painter of mothers and children, Cassatt was  
not sentimental about them. She campaigned for women's suffrage and 
said the idea for a national Mother's Day holiday was absurd. 
</P>
<P>
	Cassatt had been born to a wealthy Pittsburgh family but  
determined to earn her own way as an artist in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	She liked the proposal for the Chicago mural on ``Modern  
Woman,'' writing that the order for it came from a ``determination 
that women should be someone and not something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The prospect of contributing a major mural on the subject of  
women, to a building designed and decorated by women, and devoted 
to work by women at a venue sure to be seen by hundreds of 
thousands proved irresistible,'' wrote Judith A. Barter, curator of 
American Arts at the Art Institute of Chicago, in the catalog for 
the current show. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Impressionists discouraged her from taking on the job. She  
wrote that the idea enraged the painter Edgar Degas -- a longtime 
friend with whom some writers have seen a romantic attachment. 
Degas considered murals a kind of decoration and thought paintings 
should not be used for that. 
</P>
<P>
	American critics ridiculed the finished work. Cassatt believed  
that was because a woman had painted it. No one seems to know what 
happened to it after the exhibition closed. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she preferred to stay in France because women did not  
have to fight for recognition there if they did serious work. But a 
few years later she had a successful commercial show of her 
pictures in New York. Her work has grown in popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996 her painting ``In the Box'' set a record of $4,072,500  
for one of her works in an auction at Christie's in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Cassatt covered a range of subjects -- theater scenes; women  
taking tea, reading newspapers, at washstands; even a couple of 
flirtatious Spanish bullfighters and a few prints of nudes. 
</P>
<P>
	She rarely painted men, but the show includes two portraits of  
her brother Alexander, who became president of the Pennsylvania 
Railroad. She also advised him on collecting the work of her 
friends the Impressionists. She died in France in 1926. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander Cassatt was instrumental in shutting down Washington's  
Pennsylvania Station, which occupied the space on the Mall where 
the National Gallery now stands. The present Union Station replaced 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Mary Cassatt'' will close Sept. 6. Admission is free.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 12:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roberts Not Recognized at Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Recreating a scene from ``Notting Hill,'' Julia  
Roberts sat down to dinner with a group of friends who had no idea 
a famous Hollywood star was joining them. Things got weird though 
when one guest didn't recognize her. 
</P>
<P>
	Set up by Marie Clare magazine for an article in its July issue,  
the dinner party mirrored one in the movie that features Roberts as 
a movie star dating a London bookstore owner, except for the woman 
who had no idea who the guest of honor was. 
</P>
<P>
	``And what do you do for a living,'' she asked Roberts.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm an actress,'' Roberts replied.  
</P>
<P>
	``Anything I might have seen?'' the woman went on.  
</P>
<P>
	``How about `Pretty Woman?''' Roberts answered.  
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly it dawned on the questioner who she was talking to.  
</P>
<P>
	``She's not very good with faces,'' the woman's fiance said to  
Roberts. ``Please don't take it personally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts didn't.  
</P>
<P>
	``Why is it so weird that somebody didn't recognize me?''  
Roberts said later. ``The fact is that whenever I meet somebody, I 
say, `Nice to meet you. I'm Julia.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 00:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Astros Owner Accused Derogatory Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston Astros owner Drayton McLane went to a  
banquet to accept an award and ended up in the middle of a 
controversy with the Hispanic community. 
</P>
<P>
	Marco Camacho, vice president and general manager of KTMD-TV,  
and Rod Rodriguez, the station's sales manager, accused McLane on 
Friday of saying Hispanics couldn't understand the game of 
baseball, bought only cheap seats and didn't eat the Astrodome 
food. 
</P>
<P>
	``We asked him why he doesn't market toward Hispanics,'' Camacho  
said. ``He said it was hard to reach Hispanics because the game of 
baseball is strategy and skill and it's complicated, and that's why 
more Hispanics don't go to Astros games. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said if you gave them a basketball and told them to put the  
ball through the hoop, they can do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camacho said McLane made the comments to a small group at a  
cocktail party Thursday night prior to a banquet hosted by the 
Houston Advertising Foundation, which presented McLane with the 
Trailblazer Award for community service. 
</P>
<P>
	The station later reported McLane's comments.  
</P>
<P>
	McLane angrily denied all the charges in a statement. Then he  
cut short a South Texas vacation and returned to Houston to meet 
with reporters and further deny that he ever made any insensitive 
comments about Hispanics. 
</P>
<P>
	McLane told a different story about the conversation.  
</P>
<P>
	``They asked if there was one thing you could do for Hispanics,  
what would it be?'' McLane said. ``What I said was that the Astros 
feel we want to get them more enthused and more involved with the 
Houston Astros. Our research shows that only 8 percent of the fans 
that come to the games are Hispanics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camacho said McLane said baseball is a game of statistics and  
numbers ``and people like to follow baseball in the newspapers and 
Hispanics don't read newspapers, and when Hispanics do go, they buy 
the cheap $2 seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``My statement was, in general terms, that of all major league  
sports, the most complicated is baseball,'' McLane said. ``I say 
that to all types of groups ... You can take a basketball and get 
anyone to understand that game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camacho attended the hastily called news conference Friday and  
defended his station's actions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have witnesses who heard what he said,'' Camacho said. ``We  
are telling the truth. It's not a he said-she said. It's he 
said-they said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball commissioner Bud Selig defended McLane, calling him  
``honorable'' and ``sensitive.'' Selig dismissed the remarks by the 
TV executives as ``slander'' and said McLane has the ``full support 
of everyone in baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLane said he talked to six to eight people at a reception  
before the dinner, but denied saying anything insensitive toward 
Hispanics, who represent 22 percent of the eight-county Houston 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was never a disparaging remark pertaining to the cheap  
seats,'' McLane said. ``That was never said. The food was never 
discussed. That just wasn't a part of the conversation that we 
had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez said he heard the same comments as Camacho.  
</P>
<P>
	``He said Hispanics don't read the newspapers,'' Rodriguez said.  
``I looked at my general manager (Camacho) to see if he's really 
saying that. I told him I read newspapers. We grew up on baseball. 
It was our livelihood. Hispanics love the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLane said he'd been in business 42 years and had never had  
such an accusation, noting his companies have 11,000 employees of 
all races. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
