<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12:40 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Commanders Meet  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO and Yugoslav generals met for five  
hours in a coffeehouse on the Macedonia-Yugoslavia border today to 
work out terms of a Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo, the key to 
ending NATO's fierce bombing campaign. The two sides began meeting 
after a three-hour delay. About five hours later, the Serb 
delegation headed by car back to Yugoslav territory. A NATO 
spokesman, Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, said the Serbs needed to confer 
with Belgrade on ``a few points of detail'' in the text of the 
withdrawal plan and are expected to return later in the day. 

</P>
<P>
	Singer Mel Torme Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mel Torme, whose warm, smooth vocal delivery  
made him a hero to fellow jazz and pop singers and earned him the 
nickname ``The Velvet Fog,'' died early today at age 73. Torme, who 
had suffered a mild stroke in August 1996, was rushed from his home 
in Beverly Hills to University of California, Los Angeles at 1 a.m. 
He died of complications from the stroke at 1:45 a.m., said Rob 
Wilcox, Torme's publicist. His wife Ali and five children were at 
his side when he died, Wilcox said. 

</P>
<P>
	Graf Beats Hingis at French Open  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Steffi Graf won her sixth French Open title and the  
adoration of Roland Garros fans when she fought back to beat 
top-ranked Martina Hingis 4-6, 7-5, 6-2 in a turbulent final today. 
Hingis, who lost her second French Open final in the last three 
tournaments, received a warning and was penalized a point for 
several outbursts and was frequently booed by the center court 
fans. Graf captured the 22nd Grand Slam title of her career less 
than two weeks before her 30th birthday against the 18-year-old 
Swiss who dislodged Graf from the No. 1 ranking in March 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: End Mental Disability Myths  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to dispel myths about the mentally  
ill, President Clinton teamed up today with Tipper Gore, wife of 
his vice president, to announce a new public service campaign 
designed to change attitudes about schizophrenia, depression and 
other such maladies. ``The hard truth is, in too many of our 
communities, and in too many of our hearts, mental illness is 
misunderstood and feared,'' Clinton said in his weekly radio 
address. Mrs. Gore disclosed recently that she had battled 
depression. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Senator: Save Security Pension  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Protecting Social Security surpluses from  
other government functions is key to the retirement program's 
future, a Republican selator said today in his party's weekly radio 
address. Sen. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, co-chairman of the 
Senate Republican task force on Social Security, urged Democrats to 
support a GOP effort to legally separate the program's funds from 
the rest of the budget, preventing raids for other programs. The 
Clinton administration opposes the legislation, saying it would 
hinder the government's cash flow without helping Social Security. 

</P>
<P>
	Scotland Bank Nixes Robertson Deal  
</P>
<P>
	EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) -- The Bank of Scotland dropped plans to  
launch a U.S. telephone banking service with religious broadcaster 
Pat Robertson after he referred to Scotland as a ``dark land'' 
because it tolerates homosexuals, the bank said today. As many as 
500 accounts have been closed at the bank since March, apparently 
because of the publicity over its dealings with Robertson. In a 
joint statement with the bank, Robertson ``expressed regret that 
media comments about him had made it impossible to proceed.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Cathay, Pilots' Talks Fruitless  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways and its pilots held five  
hours of talks today without any sign of progress to end a sickout 
that has forced the carrier to cancel half its flights. After the 
discussions, Hong Kong's assistant commissioner of labor, Tsang 
Kin-woo, said there was an agreement to continue the meetings. The 
airline canceled 63 of its 119 scheduled flights today. Cathay is 
demanding that the pilots take pay cuts averaging 7 percent over 
two years in exchange for stock options and has given them until 
June 11 to either take the deal, quit or be fired. 

</P>
<P>
	School Principal Stabbed in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A man who told police he wanted more people to  
respect the Japanese flag and anthem stabbed a junior high school 
principal several times today before being arrested. The principal, 
Naoyuki Tsuda, survived the attack in his office in Osaka, and is 
not in critical condition, police said. Although the white flag 
with a red circle and the song for the emperor are widely used in 
school ceremonies, they are not officially recognized and remain 
controversial because they evoke bitter memories of Japan's 
aggression during World War II. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Agent Bought Car for Player  
</P>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Sports agent Tank Black purchased a  
$133,500 Mercedes-Benz for former Florida linebacker Jevon Kearse 
on Dec. 31, 1998, two days before the Orange Bowl, it was reported 
today. The St. Petersburg Times obtained documents from Florida's 
Division of Motor Vehicles that indicate the car was purchased in 
Kearse's name. The linebacker, a first-round draft pick by the 
Tennessee Titans, did not immediately return messages left by The 
Associated Press today. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
