<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Astros Owner Accused Derogatory Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston Astros owner Drayton McLane went to a  
banquet to accept an award and ended up in the middle of a 
controversy with the Hispanic community. 
</P>
<P>
	Marco Camacho, vice president and general manager of KTMD-TV,  
and Rod Rodriguez, the station's sales manager, accused McLane on 
Friday of saying Hispanics couldn't understand the game of 
baseball, bought only cheap seats and didn't eat the Astrodome 
food. 
</P>
<P>
	``We asked him why he doesn't market toward Hispanics,'' Camacho  
said. ``He said it was hard to reach Hispanics because the game of 
baseball is strategy and skill and it's complicated, and that's why 
more Hispanics don't go to Astros games. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said if you gave them a basketball and told them to put the  
ball through the hoop, they can do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camacho said McLane made the comments to a small group at a  
cocktail party Thursday night prior to a banquet hosted by the 
Houston Advertising Foundation, which presented McLane with the 
Trailblazer Award for community service. 
</P>
<P>
	The station later reported McLane's comments.  
</P>
<P>
	McLane angrily denied all the charges in a statement. Then he  
cut short a South Texas vacation and returned to Houston to meet 
with reporters and further deny that he ever made any insensitive 
comments about Hispanics. 
</P>
<P>
	McLane told a different story about the conversation.  
</P>
<P>
	``They asked if there was one thing you could do for Hispanics,  
what would it be?'' McLane said. ``What I said was that the Astros 
feel we want to get them more enthused and more involved with the 
Houston Astros. Our research shows that only 8 percent of the fans 
that come to the games are Hispanics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camacho said McLane said baseball is a game of statistics and  
numbers ``and people like to follow baseball in the newspapers and 
Hispanics don't read newspapers, and when Hispanics do go, they buy 
the cheap $2 seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``My statement was, in general terms, that of all major league  
sports, the most complicated is baseball,'' McLane said. ``I say 
that to all types of groups ... You can take a basketball and get 
anyone to understand that game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camacho attended the hastily called news conference Friday and  
defended his station's actions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have witnesses who heard what he said,'' Camacho said. ``We  
are telling the truth. It's not a he said-she said. It's he 
said-they said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball commissioner Bud Selig defended McLane, calling him  
``honorable'' and ``sensitive.'' Selig dismissed the remarks by the 
TV executives as ``slander'' and said McLane has the ``full support 
of everyone in baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLane said he talked to six to eight people at a reception  
before the dinner, but denied saying anything insensitive toward 
Hispanics, who represent 22 percent of the eight-county Houston 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was never a disparaging remark pertaining to the cheap  
seats,'' McLane said. ``That was never said. The food was never 
discussed. That just wasn't a part of the conversation that we 
had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez said he heard the same comments as Camacho.  
</P>
<P>
	``He said Hispanics don't read the newspapers,'' Rodriguez said.  
``I looked at my general manager (Camacho) to see if he's really 
saying that. I told him I read newspapers. We grew up on baseball. 
It was our livelihood. Hispanics love the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLane said he'd been in business 42 years and had never had  
such an accusation, noting his companies have 11,000 employees of 
all races. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
