<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay, Pilots' Talks Fruitless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways and its pilots held five  
hours of talks Saturday without any sign of progress to end a 
sickout that has forced the carrier to cancel half its flights. 
</P>
<P>
	After the discussions, Hong Kong's assistant commissioner of  
labor, Tsang Kin-woo, said there was an agreement to continue the 
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay and the pilots had no immediate comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The airline canceled 63 of its 119 scheduled flights Saturday --  
the largest number yet since pilots began calling in sick en masse 
on May 28. 
</P>
<P>
	But the carrier began accepting new bookings for flights from  
Hong Kong to Bangkok, Manila, Taipei, Kuala Lumpur and Singapore. 
Cathay halted bookings earlier in the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay is demanding that the pilots take pay cuts averaging 7  
percent over two years in exchange for stock options and has given 
them until June 11 to either take the deal, quit or be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting Thursday with Hong Kong labor leaders, Cathay  
bosses agreed to the Saturday meeting with the pilots union for the 
first time since the sickout began. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can say is that I am pleased that we'll be talking. No  
progress will be made unless we're talking and now we're talking,'' 
said John Findlay, general secretary of the Hong Kong Aircrew 
Officers Association, before the talks started. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay posted a net loss of $69 million last year, running up  
its first red ink since 1963 as passenger traffic plunged amid 
Asia's economic crisis and Hong Kong's deep recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots say that if any union member is fired in the dispute,  
they will take a strike vote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
