<DOCNO> APW19990605.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ewing Sits, Watches and Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Patrick Ewing couldn't play Saturday night. He  
couldn't run, and he certainly couldn't jump. 
</P>
<P>
	So when Larry Johnson's unlikely four-point play lifted the New  
York Knicks to a stunning 92-91 victory over the Indiana Pacers, 
Ewing left the celebrating to his teammates -- much the same way he 
has left his hopes for an NBA championship in their hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been hurt all throughout the playoffs, but he's given 110  
percent,'' said Johnson, whose 3-pointer and ensuing free throw 
with 5.7 seconds left lifted the Knicks to a 2-1 lead in the 
Eastern Conference finals. ``It's time to give it back to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing, whose black suit made him look like the world's tallest  
undertaker, wasn't dressed for the wild Madison Square Garden party 
that followed the victory. As his teammates bounced around him in 
elation on the Knicks' bench, Ewing only raised his arms toward the 
ceiling and pumped his fists. 
</P>
<P>
	With a cast on his partially torn left Achilles' tendon, that  
was the best the big man could muster. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who wound up with a game-high 26 points, made up for  
it. He ended up hugging director Spike Lee on the court after 
Indiana's Mark Jackson missed a 10-foot jumper at the end. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks responded to Ewing's pre-game call to ``get me a  
ring,'' with bench players Marcus Camby and Chris Childs 
particularly cranking up their games in Ewing's absence. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of guys had to step up with Patrick out,'' Johnson said.  
``That was our main focus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They did. In addition to Johnson's second straight 20-plus game,  
Camby -- in 33 minutes -- grabbed 11 rebounds and scored 21 points, 
including two clutch free throws to bring the Knicks within one 
with 13 seconds left. Childs had 10 assists and just a single 
turnover. 
</P>
<P>
	Camby more than made up for Ewing's missing 13.1 points and 8.7  
rebounds -- the wounded center's playoff averages. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew coming in that we were without our leader,'' Camby  
said after the game. ``We knew we had to pick up our play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And they did. Coach Jeff Van Gundy, who spent the game down the  
bench from Ewing, credited his captain with giving his teammates a 
boost despite his dark attire. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patrick was so supportive of the team -- Chris and Marcus in  
particular,'' Van Gundy said. ``I feel so happy we were able to 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The victory allowed the Knicks to keep the homecourt advantage  
going into Monday night's Game 4 at the Garden. It also continued 
their unlikely quest to get Ewing his first NBA title since 
entering the league as the overall No. 1 draft pick in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Kurt Thomas, one of several Knicks who battled Indiana  
center Rik Smits during the game, said Ewing's absence would 
continue to spur his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll just keep fighting, no matter what the situation is,''  
Thomas said. ``We'll keep fighting until the end.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
