<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yale Crew Defeats Harvard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- Yale's senior-dominated crew rowed to a  
comeback victory Saturday in the four-mile Yale-Harvard Regatta, 
finishing six seconds ahead of favored Harvard in the nation's 
oldest intercollegiate athletic event. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard led the first three miles on the wind-ruffled Thames  
River before the Eli varsity oarsmen pulled ahead and maintained a 
slim lead the rest of the way. Yale finished in 20:45, two scull 
lengths ahead of the Crimson in the 134th running of the event, 
which dates to 1852. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the only the second time Yale has defeated Harvard in the  
past 15 years and leaves the Eli trailing the series 81-53. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was delayed for several hours because of rough water on  
the Thames. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yale crew -- composed of senior coxswain Steve Pritzker,  
senior strokeman Alex Reid, senior Mark McCusker (7th man), senior 
Jim Needham (6th man), sophomore Scott Proper (5th man), junior Jim 
Donahue (4h man), senior Rob Welhoelter (3rd man), senior Hans 
VanTrotha (2nd man) and senior bowman Lucas McLoughlin -- celebrated 
long and loudly after reaching the dock. 
</P>
<P>
	Pritzker said his crew stuck to its pre-race strategy.  
</P>
<P>
	``We had a lot of guys who had been through it. Our plan was to  
keep it close the first three miles because we knew with a mile to 
go we could do it,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
