<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garcia Pulls Out of Gainer Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- IBF junior lightweight champion Roberto  
Garcia pulled out of his title defense against Derrick Gainer 
Saturday night because of a dispute over the judges, the boxer's 
manager said. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Woodworth, co-manager for Garcia, said that the IBF  
refused to provide impartial judges for the fight, which was on the 
undercard of the Roy Jones Jr.-Reggie Johnson light heavyweight 
championship bout. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariam Muhammad, executive secretary of the International Boxing  
Federation, said Garcia's managers told her Friday that they had a 
problem with one official and a change was made of the entire 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can't tell me who to have officiate, but if they have a  
problem with someone we try to accommodate them,'' she said. ``Mr. 
Woodworth came to me and I switched the officials and was told 
everything was a go. I went to bed Friday night thinking the fight 
was on and woke up Saturday morning to find out it was off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, 32-0 with 24 knockouts, won the title in a unanimous  
decision against Frank Warren on March 13, 1998. He was replaced in 
the bout by Donovan Carey of Baton Rouge, La., 15-1-1 with three 
KOs. 
</P>
<P>
	The 25-year-old Gainer of Pensacola, Fla., was 27-4 as a  
professional, with 19 knockouts, and ranked No. 2 by the IBF. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodworth said all the announced judges were from the South and  
Garcia could not risk losing the title due to an unfair decision. 
Garcia is from Oxnard, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we asked who our judges are, we were told we would have  
two Mississippi, one Louisiana and one Florida,'' Woodworth said. 
``Now, we are not trying to question the integrity of any 
commissioner or any judge, but on the surface you can't do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muhammad said she knew nothing of such concerns.  
</P>
<P>
	``What constitutes an impartial official?'' she said. ``I don't  
know what they mean by that, since we made a switch to accommodate 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woodworth said the managers were also concerned about  
allegations the IBF sold rankings and arranged fights for 
kickbacks. Federal agents raided the offices of boxing promoter Don 
King on Friday as part of an investigation the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``Robert is an undefeated champion,'' Woodworth said. ``This is  
what is wrong with boxing. All we wanted is for Gainer to pick two 
judges and us to pick two judges. All we ask for is fairness and an 
even shake, and they denied it to us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
