<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- During Jeff Gordon's transition from top  
prospect to Winston Cup champion, a Sunday at Dover Downs 
International Speedway often ended in celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	But things haven't gone so well recently on The Monster Mile for  
the 27-year-old driver from Pittsboro, Ind., who considers Dover 
his home track because sponsor DuPont is headquartered 45 minutes 
up the road in Wilmington. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon won at Dover for the first time in 1995 -- coincidentally  
the year of his first title. He returned in 1996 to win both the 
spring and fall offerings on the high-banked concrete oval. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dover is a great race track for us,'' said Gordon, who proved  
that even in defeat a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	He led 375 of 400 laps, but wound up third because he had to  
stop for fuel with eight laps left. 
</P>
<P>
	Victimized by accidents and mechanical failures this year that  
have dropped him all the way to eighth in the standings as he 
pursues a record-tying third straight title, Gordon is hoping to 
begin a turnaround Sunday in the MBNA Platinum 400. But he won't be 
greedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think anything in the top five would make it a successful  
weekend,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HEADING HOME:* Three-time Winston Cup champion Darrell Waltrip,  
whose 84 career victories are the most among active drivers, failed 
to make the field for the MBNA 400. It was only the second time in 
his 28-year career that Waltrip has been sent home. 
</P>
<P>
	The last of his 84 career victories came in the 1992 Southern  
500, 207 races ago. Waltrip, who also failed to make the field in 
Concord, N.C., in October 1997, has been qualifying often as a 
result of provisionals. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is out of them for now, and will have to drive fast  
enough to get in for the next three races. He had two shots this 
weekend, but failed to go fast enough either Friday or Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip was joined on the sidelines by Hut Stricklin and rookie  
Buckshot Jones, who also failed to qualify Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CRASH IRVAN:* Ernie Irvan, whose once-promising career has  
degenerated into an almost-weekly crashfest, was busy Saturday. He 
was involved in two accidents while driving in the MBNA Platinum 
200 Busch Grand National event, then did some meaningful damage. 
</P>
<P>
	At the beginning of ``Happy Hour,'' the final practice for  
Winston Cup drivers competing in Sunday's MBNA Platinum 400, Irvan 
wrecked again. He totaled his Pontiac when it spun into the 
frontstretch wall at Dover Downs International Speedway. An oil 
line came loose, quickly engulfing the engine compartment in 
flames, but Irvan escaped without injury. 
</P>
<P>
	He was in his backup car a few minutes after the practice crash,  
and finished the session without another mishap. Because his 
primary car was withdrawn, Irvan will fall to the rear of the 
43-car field Sunday. He had earned the 29th starting position. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan was a factor in the championship race in 1994 until he  
crashed during practice at Michigan Speedway. He had a major head 
injury, and was out of action for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 40-year-old driver from Salinas, Calif., has 15 career  
victories, three since his return late in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SOME BAD NAMES:* Dover Downs International Speedway has been  
called many things -- often unprintable ones -- in its 31 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Park is aware of most of them, and says they are  
justified. 
</P>
<P>
	``This place has more nicknames than any track we go to,'' he  
said. ``There's The Monster Mile and White Lighting. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you notice, none of them are nice, soothing names, either.  
There is good reason for that. I think all the names are designed 
to intimidate the drivers.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIT STOPS:* A victory by Jeff Gordon, Terry Labonte or Wally  
Dallenbach would give Hendrick Motorsports seven at Dover, tying 
the Wood Brothers for the most in track history. The Woods haven't 
been to the winner's circle at Dover since the late Neil Bonnett 
won the 1981 fall race. ... Ken Schrader, a winner of the spring 
race in 1991, hasn't prevailed anywhere since -- a drought of 247 
starts. ... Bill Elliott's losing streak now stands at 139 races 
... Kenny Wallace didn't have any fun last year on The Monster 
Mile. He had an accident and finished 40th in the spring race, then 
blew an engine, finished just two laps and was last in the fall 
event. ... Fords took five of the top seven spots in both Dover 
races last year. ... Sweeps are no rarity at Dover. Six times in 
track history -- most recently by Jeff Gordon in 1996 -- a driver has 
won both the spring and fall events. ... Rookie points leader Tony 
Stewart is a shocking fifth overall in the Winston Cup standings. 
No rookie has finished the season in the top 10 since Jody Ridley 
wound up seventh in 1980. ... Terry Labonte will extend the career 
record for most consecutive Winston Cup starts when he takes the 
green flag Sunday for the 615th straight time. The rear fenders on 
Rick Mast's Ford bear this inscription: ``Guess Who, Ha! Ha! Ha! 
Ha!'' That's a teaser for a sponsorship deal expected to be 
announced next weekend at Michigan Speedway. ... James Ince, crew 
chief for Rich Bickle, and Jeff Buice, who calls the shots for 
Jerry Nadeau, have been fined $2,500 by NASCAR for drilling holes 
in the frames of their cars to lighten them prior to the Coca-Cola 
600 last Sunday in Concord, N.C. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
