<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saudis, Mexicans Discuss Oil Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Mexico's energy minister met with  
his Saudi Arabian counterpart Saturday and discussed the world oil 
market and greater cooperation between the two producers, the 
Mexican energy minister, Luis Tellez, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tellez said that he and the Saudi oil minister, Ali Naimi, did  
not discuss the possibility of further production cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico joined the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries  
and other non-OPEC producers in a March agreement to cut more than 
2.1 million barrels a day from world oil supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, scheduled to run from April 1, 1999 until the end  
of March, bolstered depressed oil prices that fell to a record low 
of $10 per barrel. London's benchmark Brent blend futures were at 
$15.20 a barrel late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tellez and Naimi ``reiterated the firm commitment of their  
governments with the supply reduction agreements and expressed 
their will to continue with the agreements in terms of timeframe 
and quantities,'' said a statement issued after their meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	It said both ministers believed that current prices, which have  
shored up after rising sharply, would improve even more. 
</P>
<P>
	Tellez said after the meeting that he and Naimi, whose country  
is the biggest OPEC producer, estimated near-full compliance in May 
production by all members. 
</P>
<P>
	Tellez, who arrived Friday, is also expected to visit Kuwait.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 14:15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gay Philanthropist Named Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The controversy over the new U.S.  
ambassador to Luxembourg looms larger than the tiny country. 
</P>
<P>
	James C. Hormel, appointed to the post Friday by President  
Clinton, has been dean of the University of Chicago law school and 
has built a reputation as one of San Francisco's most generous 
philanthropists. But Hormel, who has diplomatic experience, is 
likely to be remembered less for his diplomatic skills than as the 
nation's first openly gay ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's appointment, made while the Senate was in recess,  
angered Catholics and religious conservatives by bypassing senators 
who had held up Hormel's nomination since October 1997. They fear 
that Hormel, who used part of his family's Hormel food fortune to 
help create the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay and 
lesbian political group, will promote a radical agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	The Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights opposes  
Hormel because he has refused to condemn the Sisters of Perpetual 
Indulgence, an irreverent group of habit-wearing drag queens. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the man's sexual orientation, but his record of  
anti-Catholic bigotry,'' said William Donohue, president of the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	Others, however, acknowledge that sexual orientation is the  
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that by forcing Americans to be represented by a  
radical homosexual activist like Hormel, Clinton is showing his 
contempt for traditional morality, marriage, sexual fidelity and 
any concept of honor,'' said Robert Knight with the Washington, 
D.C.-based Family Research Council, a religious lobby. ``Who's he 
going to appoint next? Larry Flynt as ambassador to the Vatican?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hormel, 66, who twice was named to U.S. delegations to the  
United Nations, made few public comments during the long nomination 
fight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hardly view myself as a 'radical,''' he wrote to Sen. Gordon  
Smith, R-Ore., a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	But in 1996 he described himself as a mentor to homosexuals,  
``part elder statesman for a constituency that is still in its 
adolescence in terms of experiencing its wisdom and empowerment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hormel's friends call him charming and funny, a good listener  
and a consummate host. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has a real sense of foreign relations, always has,'' says  
Alice Turner, who was married to Hormel from 1955 to '65. ``He is 
extraordinarily well-qualified -- overqualified -- for this 
appointment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hormel's nomination cleared the Senate Foreign Relations  
Committee in 1997 and secured bipartisan Senate support. Officials 
in Luxembourg, where 97 percent of the population of 425,000 is 
Catholic, said it would welcome Hormel as ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who has compared  
homosexuality to vices such as kleptomania and sex addiction, 
refused to schedule a floor vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``On one hand, you have these anti-gay senators saying we don't  
need legislation to protect gays and lesbians but you have the 
United States Senate discriminating against someone because he's 
gay,'' says David Smith of the Human Rights Campaign. ``It was very 
un-American and unfair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friends say that, far from being a radical activist, Hormel is a  
devoted family man, to his partner, Timothy Wu, and to his children 
-- four daughters and a son, and 13 grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``My father has better family values than most parents I know.  
He is very dedicated to his family,'' says James Hormel Jr., who 
moved to San Francisco to live near his father. ``Our family is 
different, yes, but it is extremely strong. We love each other very 
much.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 08:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Commanders Meet  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO and Yugoslav commanders met at a  
cafe today along the Kosovo-Macedonia border for crucial talks 
establishing the precise terms for the withdrawal of Serb troops 
from Kosovo -- a key condition before NATO halts the bombardment of 
Yugoslavia. Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain, representing NATO, 
was joined at the Europe coffeehouse by a delegation of Yugoslav 
generals who arrived three hours late. Alliance officials said 
there would be no negotiations -- just details spelling out the 
conditions and logistics of the pullout. NATO spokesman Jamie Shea 
stressed that withdrawing Yugoslav troops would be open to 
airstrikes if they commit any violence during their retreat. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: End Mental Disability Myths  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to dispel myths about the mentally  
ill, President Clinton teamed up today with Tipper Gore, wife of 
his vice president, to announce a new public service campaign 
designed to change attitudes about schizophrenia, depression and 
other such maladies. ``The hard truth is, in too many of our 
communities, and in too many of our hearts, mental illness is 
misunderstood and feared,'' Clinton said in his weekly radio 
address. Clinton asked Mrs. Gore to join him as a prelude to the 
first White House conference on mental illness Monday. Mrs. Gore, 
wife of vice President Al Gore, disclosed recently that she had 
battled depression. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA To Enforce Crew Rest Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of the Federal Aviation  
Administration has told the American Airlines pilots union that the 
agency will begin strictly enforcing crew rest regulations by the 
end of the year, the union says. That word yesterday came three 
days after an American jet crashed on landing in Little Rock, Ark., 
at the end of a long day for the two-member cockpit crew, although 
the FAA said the stepped-up enforcement is not related to the 
accident. Under federal law, airline pilots cannot fly more than 
eight hours in a 24-hour period. 

</P>
<P>
	Scotland Bank Nixes Robertson Deal  
</P>
<P>
	EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) -- The Bank of Scotland dropped plans to  
launch a U.S. telephone banking service with religious broadcaster 
Pat Robertson after he referred to Scotland as a ``dark land'' 
because it tolerates homosexuals, the bank said today. As many as 
500 accounts have been closed at the bank since March, apparently 
because of the publicity over its dealings with Robertson. In a 
joint statement with the bank, Robertson ``expressed regret that 
media comments about him had made it impossible to proceed.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Return To Poland  
</P>
<P>
	GDANSK, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II began his longest  
pilgrimage to his native Poland today at the site of one of his 
papacy's greatest triumphs: the Baltic coast city where the 
Solidarity movement that toppled communism was born. Focusing on a 
theme expected to dominate the 13-day visit to 20 cities and towns, 
the pontiff spoke of pride in democratic Poland's economic 
development. 

</P>
<P>
	South Dakota Tornado Kills One  
</P>
<P>
	PIERRE, S.D. (AP) -- One person is dead and several are reported  
injured after the tiny town of Oglala on the Pine Ridge Indian 
Reservation was hit by a tornado last night. National Weather 
Service spotters reported at least three tornadoes near Pine Ridge, 
and severe storms were reported in other parts of the state. A 
46-year-old man was killed and six people are missing, including a 
baby living in with the man. ``Maybe 20 mobile homes were destroyed 
and 50 other residences were damaged,''John Mousseau of the Pine 
Ridge Police Department said today. 

</P>
<P>
	School Principal Stabbed in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A man who told police he wanted more people to  
respect the Japanese flag and anthem stabbed a junior high school 
principal several times today before being arrested. The principal, 
Naoyuki Tsuda, survived the attack in his office in Osaka, and is 
not in critical condition, police said. Although the white flag 
with a red circle and the song for the emperor are widely used in 
sports events and school ceremonies, they are not officially 
recognized and remain controversial because they evoke bitter 
memories of Japan's aggression during World War II. 

</P>
<P>
	Hingis Takes First Set of Final  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Top-ranked Martina Hingis leads five-time champion  
Steffi Graf 6-4 after the first set of the women's final today at 
the French Open. The start of the match was delayed more than an 
hour because of rain and Graf was in trouble quickly, losing the 
first two points and then facing two break points. Earlier today, 
Andre Agassi completed a rain-delayed semifinal victory over 
Dominik Hrbaty to reach the final of the French Open for the third 
time. Tomorrow, he will meet Andrei Medvedev, who is the 
lowest-ranked player in the Open era to reach the French Open 
final. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 08:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Agent Bought Car for Player </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Sports agent Tank Black purchased a  
$133,500 Mercedes-Benz for former Florida linebacker Jevon Kearse 
on Dec. 31, 1998, two days before the Orange Bowl, it was reported 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Petersburg Times obtained documents from Florida's  
Division of Motor Vehicles that indicate the car was purchased in 
Kearse's name. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper reported that Kearse's signature appears on an  
odometer disclosure statement dated Dec. 31. DMV papers identify 
Kearse as the owner of the car and indicate a lien dated Dec. 31. 
The vehicle's registration application lists Kearse as the car's 
owner and the date of acquisition as Dec. 31. The notarized title 
lists Dec. 31 as the date the title was transferred from an Atlanta 
dealership to Kearse. 
</P>
<P>
	Kearse drove the car to a Jan. 5 news conference in Gainesville  
to announce he would forgo his senior season to enter the NFL 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The linebacker, a first-round draft pick by the Tennessee  
Titans, did not immediately return telephone messages left by The 
Associated Press on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Leonard Mungo said Black bought the car, but it was not  
given to Kearse until Jan. 5, three days after his eligibility had 
expired. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tank, as you know, purchases cars for all his clients,'' Mungo  
said. ``That kind of vehicle was a rare vehicle and he knows his 
clients are always looking for those kinds of vehicles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mungo claims Kearse didn't know the car existed until his  
eligibility was complete and there was no agreement to provide the 
car to Kearse in exchange for him signing with Black. He said 
Kearse's signatures on the documents dated Dec. 31, 1998 may have 
been forged. 
</P>
<P>
	A salesman at RBM of Atlanta, the dealership that sold Black the  
Mercedes, said he has been issued a subpoena in the investigation 
and declined comment. Asked if he remembered anything about the New 
Year's Eve transaction, salesman John Johnson told the newspaper, 
``I do, but I'm under subpoena.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA's Bill Saum, who investigates problems involving agents  
and gambling, confirmed that Kearse would have been ineligible for 
the Orange Bowl if an agent had helped him buy a car. But he said 
Florida would not be in violation unless school officials were 
aware and let Kearse play anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Saum said that even if Kearse had the car in Miami before the  
bowl game, it may not have been obvious to UF officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``It depends on where the car was,'' Saum said. ``Just because  
it might have been in the same city as the bowl game, you can't 
jump to the conclusion that someone should have seen it and made 
some decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL Players Association has filed a disciplinary complaint  
against Black accusing him of improper dealings with former Florida 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	University police are investigating the Columbia, S.C.-based  
agent, as well. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, former linebacker Johnny Rutledge admitted taking  
$500-per-month payments from Black over the span of a year. 
Rutledge said Reggie McGrew and Kearse have admitted the same under 
sworn depositions. 
</P>
<P>
	Mungo said Kearse and Rutledge first testified they had not  
taken payments, but were coerced by investigators into changing 
their testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Violating Florida's agent law is a crime punishable by up to  
five years in prison and a $5,000 fine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 16:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Women's Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST POINT, Miss. (AP) -- Even after a 2-over 74 on Saturday that  
dropped her 11 strokes behind the leader, Si Re Pak isn't ready to 
give up her reign as U.S. Women's Open champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, not yet. Open not over. I have 18 holes left, who knows.  
Somebody could shoot low score. It could be me,'' Pak, the 
21-year-old South Korean, said after her worst round at Old Waverly 
Golf Club. ``One more day ... I still have chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from bogeys at Nos. 2 and 5, Pak had pars the rest of the  
way Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pak, who beat Jenny Chuasiriporn in a 20-hole playoff for last  
year's Open title, opened this year's tournament with rounds of 67 
and 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Since following her U.S. Women's Open championship with two  
victories last July, Pak hasn't had won or even had a top 10 
finish. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LUCKY BOUNCE:* Karrie Webb got a lucky bounce at No. 18 on  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitting a 5-iron out of the rough about 169 yards from the pin,  
Webb thought she had left the ball short. Instead, it barely caught 
the edge of a brick wall bulkhead separating the green from Lake 
Waverly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a lucky break. You know, sometimes you get those,  
sometimes you don't,'' Webb said. ``I was really just trying to fly 
through the front of the green to try and carry that trap. Just 
really didn't come at it cleanly at all and thought it was in the 
water pretty much the whole way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ball bounced high off the brick, over the bunker fronting  
the green and rolled into the fringe on the opposite side. She 
chipped within 4 feet and saved par to finish with a 4-under 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb is at 8 under for the championship, seven strokes off the  
lead. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SIGHT UNSEEN:* Before the U.S. Women's Open started, Lori Kane  
had never played the last five holes at Old Waverly Golf Club. 
</P>
<P>
	It obviously hasn't affected her through three rounds.  
</P>
<P>
	At 11-under 205, Kane is tied with Kelli Kuehne for second  
place, four strokes behind Juli Inkster. 
</P>
<P>
	Kane has played holes No. 14 through 18 in 5 under this week.  
She was bogey free through that stretch until getting to No. 17, a 
183-yard par-3, on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kane had planned to play just nine holes each of the first two  
days after getting to West Point and then play 18 holes on 
Wednesday, the day before the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``My clubs didn't arrive until Monday late, so the nine holes  
was out. I stuck with my game plan because I wanted to get more 
rest,'' Kane said. 
</P>
<P>
	After playing nine holes Tuesday, rain and lightning delays  
Wednesday limited Kane to just 13 holes. She then walked the last 
five holes, and played them for the first time in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BIG SUPPORT:* Kelli Kuehne had some big support during the  
third round. 
</P>
<P>
	Her fiancee, Jay Humphrey, was in the gallery. And he wasn't  
hard to pick out of the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Humphrey is a 6-foot-7, 300-pound offensive tackle from Texas  
who was drafted in April by the Minnesota Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AMATEUR ACES:* Amateur champion Grace Park enters the final  
round of the Women's Open tied for 10th, even after a 1-over 73 on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20-year-old Park, who is playing her final tournament as an  
amateur, earned a full exemption into the Open as only the second 
player ever to win golf's three major women's amateur titles in the 
same year. 
</P>
<P>
	Park is at 6 under, five strokes off the lead. The only other  
amateur to make the cut, Kellee Booth, shot a 2-under 70 Saturday 
and is even through 36 holes. 
</P>
<P>
	Pak and Booth were the only of 12 amateurs in the Open to make  
the cut. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FELLOW AUSSIES:* Five Australians made the cut at the U.S.  
Women's Open. Only one, Wendy Doolan, wasn't paired with a fellow 
Aussie during the third round. 
</P>
<P>
	Mardi Lunn and Alison Munt, who both started at 1 under, were  
grouped together. Webb and Rachel Hetherington, both at 4 under, 
played in another group. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb had the best day by an Aussie with a 4-under 68, while  
Hetherington had a 76. Munt shot a 71, three strokes better than 
Lunn. Doolan shot a 73. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *UP AND DOWN:* Maria Hjorth has U.S. Women's Open best 17  
birdies, one more than leader Juli Inkster, but Hjorth is 11 
strokes off the lead at 4-under 212 after three rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to her birdies, Hjorth has 11 bogeys and a double  
bogey. Inkster, on the other hand, has had just one bogey, that at 
No. 3 during the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Hjorth countered seven birdies with three bogeys  
and a double bogey to finish with a 2-under 70. That followed 
rounds of 73 and 69. 
  	   	
</P>
