<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pantani Barred From Tour of Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADONNA DI CAMPIGLIO, Italy (AP) -- Marco Pantani was barred from  
the Tour of Italy Saturday, two stages from his second consecutive 
triumph, after tests showed unusually high levels of red blood 
cells. 
</P>
<P>
	The high counts can signal the use of the banned growth hormone  
EPO, but also can occur naturally. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian television quoted the team as saying dehydration and the  
high altitude of Friday's leg of the race might be responsible for 
Pantani's reading. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani, leaving his hotel two hours after the 21st stage of the  
Giro had started without him, said he could not understand what had 
happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry for cycling ... but there is something strange in  
this affair,'' the 29-year-old Italian said, saying a blood test 
Friday night showed no irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	``This morning, I had a bitter surprise,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Italy's Tg2 quoted him, off-camera, as saying he might retire.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have restarted after serious accidents ... but this time my  
morale has really hit the bottom,'' Pantani said when asked about 
the question of retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	International Cycling Union doctors performed the tests on  
Pantani and other cyclists hours before the start of the 21st stage 
of the cycling marathon. The top 15 competitors in overall 
standings were reportedly tested. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani's count was red blood cell count 52, Italian media said.  
The UIC maximum is 50. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Pantani was prevented from starting in the leg and  
barred from competing for 15 days, organizers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the law. We had to stop him,'' Hein Verbruggen, head of  
the UIC, told Italy's ANSA news agency. ``It's a hard blow for 
cycling because the No. 1 has been hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All competitors had been tested before the start of the race in  
Agrigento, Sicily, last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Two unheralded cyclists, Nicola Loda and Javier Ochoa Palacios,  
were stopped by UIC doctors then because of high red blood cells 
count. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani, one of the best world climbers, had virtually clinched  
the Tour of Italy on Friday by winning his fourth stage at this 
resort in the Dolomite mountains, extending his lead by more than 5 
1-2 minutes over the closest rival, Paolo Savoldelli. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's stage started without the pink jersey since  
Salvodelli, the new leader, refused to wear it. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the events of Saturday ``the worst thing that could  
have happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Savoldelli now holds a 34-second lead over compatriot Ivan  
Gotti, the 1997 Giro winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani had won both the Giro and the Tour of France last year --  
the latter rocked by a doping scandal that took the prestigious 
French race to the brink of suspension. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
