<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. St. Stars Plead Not Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Michigan State University basketball stars  
Mateen Cleaves and Antonio Smith pleaded not guilty to misdemeanor 
charges of larceny. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair were formally charged Friday in connection with  
stealing a 40-ounce bottle of beer from an East Lansing 7-Eleven. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've waived arraignment and the next step is the pre-trial,''  
their attorney, Brian Jeffries, told the Lansing State Journal 
after submitting their waiver forms Friday morning in East Lansing 
District Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The players did not appear in court.  
</P>
<P>
	The arrest warrants were issued Wednesday -- seven weeks after  
police pulled over the two players who led the Spartans to the 
Final Four in the NCAA Tournament this year, Michigan State 
University's first trip since 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Their vehicle matched the description of one reportedly involved  
in a store theft about 2 a.m. on April 14. Smith was arrested on 
two traffic warrants that night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingham County Prosecutor Stuart Dunnings III said it took seven  
weeks to issue the other warrants because police needed time to 
investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves, a 21-year-old two-time All-American, and Smith, 23,  
face misdemeanor charges of larceny of property worth less than 
$200. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, accused of breaking open the 7-Eleven's cooler door lock,  
also faces a charge of malicious destruction of property. If 
convicted, the pair face up to 93 days in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released Wednesday, Michigan State basketball  
coach Tom Izzo said he hadn't seen the complaint or the police 
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is my understanding that the matter will be dealt with in  
the courts and after the judicial process runs its course, I'll 
take appropriate action,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defendants in certain misdemeanor cases are allowed to file  
arraignment waivers and not appear in person, as long as their 
rights are communicated to them through their lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	A date has not been set for the pre-trial conference.  
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves chose to stay at Michigan State University for his  
senior year next fall, passing up an opportunity last month to 
declare for the NBA Draft. Smith, the Spartans No. 3 career 
rebounder, completed his eligibility in March and some draft 
analysts project him as a possible second-round pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Both players are from Flint, Mich. and were captains during the  
1998-99 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Michigan State player, Jason Klein, was in the car with  
Smith and Cleaves when police pulled it over. No warrant has been 
issued for his arrest. Also in the vehicle was a female who was 
ticketed for underage drinking. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
