<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crop Subsidy Changes Awaited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Producers and lawmakers are awaiting word from  
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman on sweeping changes he is 
considering in a crop subsidy program that has ballooned in size. 
</P>
<P>
	``Loan deficiency'' payouts occur when commodity prices drop  
below a so-called ``loan rate'' -- a predetermined price set by the 
department. 
</P>
<P>
	These payments vary widely from county to county due to a number  
of factors, and Glickman wants the payments equalized, which could 
cost nearly $400 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got places in this country where you get an LDP of 30  
cents and you go 15 miles and get 70 cents,'' Glickman said in an 
interview. ``That's not fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He pledged Thursday that a decision on whether to overhaul the  
payment system would come within 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Created to ensure minimum crop income for farmers, the subsidy  
program kicked in last year when the Asian economic crisis and a 
worldwide grain glut caused U.S. prices to plummet. Farmers 
collected $2.89 billion for last year's crops under the program, 
and the 1999 cost will soar to nearly $5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the 1996 farm bill was written, nobody really thought  
that LDP would turn out to do very much because people believed the 
market would go up forever and worldwide demand would go up 
forever,'' Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today almost every farmer in America is getting an LDP  
payment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It rivals the Agriculture Department's largest program, the  
``market transition'' payments established in the 1996 farm law to 
wean producers off government support programs. That program cost 
the government $5.6 billion last year alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Commodity groups and members of Congress have criticized the  
Agriculture Department for what they call a rush to transform a 
complicated system. Many have accused USDA of being too secretive 
about the proposed changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not secrecy,'' Glickman said, arguing that lawmakers  
have been briefed all along and that some farm news services are 
``kind of whipping the issue up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact, however, is that we do have to ensure that we get  
the word out clearly,'' he said. ``I think if we do nothing, these 
same congressmen and senators who are asking us to slow down are 
going to get barraged this year from people who are treated in what 
they say is a discriminatory fashion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both USDA and the White House's Office of Management and Budget  
are reviewing the plan for a uniform, national rate structure. 
</P>
<P>
	The reasons for county-to-county variances are complicated: Each  
weekday, the department calculates both loan rates and prices for 
major commodities in every county in the nation. The amount of a 
loan deficiency payment is the difference between the loan rate and 
posted price on a given day. 
</P>
<P>
	Another major factor is the extra transportation cost the  
farther a county is from a terminal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture Department recently distributed examples using  
data from 10 dates over the past year comparing current rates with 
a proposed national rate. While the outlook for corn growers was 
rosy, according to that scenario, the picture for wheat producers 
wasn't so good. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to work pretty good for us on spring wheat,  
but it looks like durum's going to get clobbered,'' said Lance 
Gabe, executive director of the North Dakota Grain Growers 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Average payments could go up for some but down for others, and  
``people don't want to be on the wrong side of the average,'' said 
Gabe, whose state rivals Kansas as the nation's leading wheat 
producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Glickman said he is under enormous pressure from Corn Belt  
producers to equalize the loan rates, and it is farmers in those 
states -- Iowa, Indiana, Illinois, Nebraska and parts of Kansas -- 
who likely would benefit the most. 
</P>
<P>
	But tentative analysis suggests no commodity would be worse off  
under a new system, the secretary said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers I have seen show that by and large, no state  
suffers any material harm,'' said Glickman. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
