<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts From Torme Autobiography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	From Mel Torme's autobiography ``It Wasn't All Velvet'':  

</P>
<P>
	``I have always felt that the `reading' of a lyric by a singer  
is concomitant with the reading of good poetry. One doesn't rattle 
off the lines, singsong style, merely to serve the rhyming. The 
`reason,' the natural sense of the lyric lines, (is) of paramount 
importance, as far as I'm concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	(After working with Marilyn Monroe on a song and skit they did  
together): ``She walked to the end of the hallway. The elevator 
came. She turned toward me and said, `I mean it. I love you.' Then 
she was gone. I knew she did not mean `I love you' in any literal 
sense. She was in love with DiMaggio. She `loved' me for treating 
her like something more than a glossily packaged piece of meat. For 
taking the time to help make her look good in front of a large 
audience. For caring about what she read and thought and felt.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	(On a career slump in the 1960s): ``There comes a time when,  
with your hopes unfulfilled and your expectations diminished, you 
begin to think, `Is this all there is?' ... Trouble is, giving in 
means giving up, at least to me it does. I always believed there 
were better times a-comin' for what I still doggedly called `my 
career.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
