<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yagli Wins Belmont Stakes Undercard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Yagli made a triumphant return to the race track  
on Saturday, sweeping past Middlesex Drive in the deep stretch to 
win the $300,000 Manhattan Handicap on Belmont Stakes day. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third of four stakes races leading up to Charismatic's  
bid for the Triple Crown in the Belmont, Yagli made a strong move 
at the top of the stretch and won by 2 1/2 lengths over Federal Trial, 
with Middlesex Drive another neck back. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Yagli's first start since Feb. 6, when the 6-year-old  
trained by Hall of Famer Bill Mott won the Gulfstream Park 
Breeders' Cup Handicap. Mott elected to give Yagli a rest as he 
prepares his horse for the Breeders' Cup Turf in November at 
Gulfstream Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Yagli covered 1 1/4 miles on the inner turf course in 1:58 2-5,  
giving jockey Jerry Bailey his fourth victory on the undercard 
leading to the Belmont. He was aboard Silverbulletday in the 
Belmont Stakes. The winner, who went off at 2-5, returned $4.30, 
$2.90 and $2.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Yagli won for the ninth time in 19 career starts and earned  
$180,000 for owner Allen Paulson. Bailey also won aboard Dance 
Master in the first race, Durmiente in the third and Yes It's True 
in the $150,000 Riva Ridge. 
</P>
<P>
	In the $150,000 True North Handicap, 26-1 longshot Kashatreya  
overtook favored Artax in the stretch. The winner returned $55, 
$13.80 and $7.10. Artax was second, and The Trader's Echo third. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes It's True held the lead through the stretch and beat Lion  
Hearted by a length in the Riva Ridge, giving trainer D. Wayne 
Lukas his second win of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Owned by Padua Stable, Yes It's True made his first start since  
a victory three weeks ago in the Maryland Breeders' Cup Handicap on 
Preakness day, a race in which a crazed fan walked onto the track, 
tried to punch at a few horses, including Artax, and nearly was 
trampled as the horses narrowly avoided him in the stretch run. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes It's True, the 3-5 favorite in the 10-horse field, covered  
seven furlongs in 1:22 1-5 and returned $3.50, $2.90 and $2.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Cozy Blues, a 10-1 shot, won the $150,000 Just A Game Breeders'  
Cup by a neck over UR Unforgetable. The winner, trained by James 
Bond, paid $21.40, $8.90 and $6.20, and covered a mile in 1:33 1-5. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
