<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Release Handle in Trunks Recommended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- There should be a handle inside car trunks  
that would allow children who inadvertently lock themselves inside 
to escape, a government-appointed panel says. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking to prevent the deaths of children, the panel recommended  
all new cars have a release mechanism inside the trunk by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration created the  
panel to study the problem because 11 children died last year after 
accidentally locking themselves into trunks in the extreme summer 
heat, often while playing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Expert Panel on Trunk Entrapment, composed of  
representatives from industry, medical and consumer groups, also is 
encouraging automakers to voluntarily develop kits for trunk 
release handles for cars already on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the panel's other recommendations, outlined in a report  
obtained by The Associated Press: 
</P>
<P>
	--Educational outreach to parents so children understand the  
trunk is not a safe place to play. 
</P>
<P>
	--Trunk safety information on warning labels and owners manuals  
in cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Several automakers have taken steps to make trunk handles  
available. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. has a trunk-release kit at dealerships that  
can be installed as optional equipment. GM's yellow handle is 
illuminated in the dark cargo area. There is a separate mechanism 
for the trunk latch to prevent the trunk from shutting unless an 
adult manually resets it. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Co. will have a T-shaped handle that glows inside the  
trunk as a standard feature on its 2000 models. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1970, 1,175 people have been victims in 992 trunk  
entrapments -- mostly adults locked in by criminals or children who 
unintentionally locked themselves in, according to the panel study. 
At least 260 people have died. 
</P>
<P>
	The majority of the deaths involved a violent abduction, the  
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel asked criminology experts whether criminals might  
become more violent toward victims if they knew there was a trunk 
handle. The study concluded ``criminal behavior could not be 
predicted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The panel therefore concluded that its focus should be on  
preventing unintentional entrapments, particularly in the case of 
children,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Janette Fennell, head of the San Francisco-based Trunk Releases  
Urgently Needed Coalition, said handles must be mandatory because 
getting trapped in a trunk is a serious problem, but people do not 
prepare for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody thinks it's going to happen to them,'' said Ms.  
Fennell, who was robbed and stuffed in a trunk at gunpoint along 
with her husband in 1995. ``It's rare to get out of a trunk without 
problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They managed to escape after they dug into the trunk's  
upholstery and found the release cable. However, Ms. Fennell said 
25 percent to 30 percent of the victims entrapped in trunks are 
seriously injured, mostly because of extreme temperatures and lack 
of ventilation. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
