<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Attendants Allow Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Northwest Airlines flight attendants, who  
have been without a contract since 1996, voted overwhelmingly 
Saturday to authorize their union to call a strike if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives from Teamsters Local 2000 in Detroit counted  
8,735 ballots, about 93 percent of eligible voters, said Danny 
Campbell, the local secretary-treasurer. Only 49 flight attendants 
voted against strike authorization, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen it coming for a long time. Our employees went  
through three years of pay cuts and have been at the bargaining 
table for three years,'' Campbell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest spokesman Jon Austin said the vote was expected.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's very rare that there isn't such a vote in the negotiating  
process in this industry,'' Austin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, flight attendants said they would ask to be released  
from contract talks if they don't make progress during the next 
round of negotiations slated for this week. 
</P>
<P>
	If the National Mediation Board releases the attendants from  
talks, that would start a 30-day cooling-off period before a strike 
could begin. Northwest is recovering from a pilots' strike last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators for the Eagan-based carrier and its 11,000 flight  
attendants broke off talks in Washington on May 22 after the two 
sides disagreed over pay comparisons. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Brotherhood of Teamsters Local 2000 wants its  
members to receive pay comparable to that at Delta Air Lines, whose 
flight attendants are considered the industry's best paid. 
According to the Teamsters, Northwest doesn't want Delta's numbers 
used in the talks. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
