<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mia Hamm Deals With Celebrity Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- In another heady week for the U.S. women's  
soccer team, Mia Hamm found there was honor -- and humor -- in being 
the star. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm, the most famous women's player in the world, was due to  
have a massive building dedicated in her name at Nike's world 
headquarters in suburban Portland. So the day before, her team 
taped up signs around the hotel declaring the Mia Hamm Drinking 
Fountain, the Mia Hamm Supply Closet and the Mia Hamm Thermostat. 
</P>
<P>
	The ribbing provided relief for the group of 20 women who will  
face growing scrutiny as the favorites to win the third women's 
World Cup this summer. The U.S. team plays its first match June 19 
at Giants Stadium against Denmark. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's kind of this anxious excitement about it, and everyone  
can't wait to get started,'' Hamm said as the team prepared for 
Sunday's exhibition against Canada, its final World Cup tune-up. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm seems uncomfortable being the poster girl for women's  
soccer but gamely carries on. A national TV ad depicts her 
dribbling a soccer ball past Michael Jordan, and ends with her 
flipping the superstar over her shoulder in a textbook Karate move. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentiment -- women are just as competitive as men -- does more  
than just sell Gatorade. Hamm sees the World Cup as an opportunity 
for the United States to inspire women and girls, in this country 
and in others. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always felt the potential of the sport was limitless, and I  
still think it is,'' she said. ``We've been role models since Day 
1, ever since we were in college. I think we just are now in a 
larger scale. So everyone's kind of taking this responsibility very 
seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm has talked of wanting to spend more time with her husband,  
Christiaan, and the rest of her family. But she said she hasn't 
decided what to do with her career after the World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still want to play,'' she said. ``I'm looking at the (2000)  
Olympics, then after that who knows?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm played in the inaugural women's cup in 1991, which the U.S.  
team won, and in 1995, when the Americans finished third. Since 
taking the gold medal at the 1996 Olympics, the United States has 
steadily become the dominant team in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	The team is 14-2-1 this season, with both losses coming to  
China, the top-seeded team in Group D. It is 8-1 in a 10-game 
``Road to Pasadena'' exhibition tour, outscoring opponents 37-3. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to think we're far and away the best in the world,''  
U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said. ``But there are other teams that are 
certainly capable of beating us on any given day and winning this 
World Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a 3-0 victory over Brazil May 22 in Orlando, Fla., Hamm  
scored her 108th career international goal, the most by any player. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States defeated Australia 4-0 Thursday in a  
closed-door game at Nike. DiCicco started eight reserves, with 
midfielder Kristine Lilly, defender Brandi Chastain and forward 
Tiffeny Milbrett the only regular starters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The object is to keep improving right through the World Cup,''  
DiCicco said of Sunday's match against Canada, which last lost its 
last 12 matches to the Americans dating to July 1986. ``So the most 
important thing now is to have a good game and stay healthy, and 
get three points June 19.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite rain in the forecast, about 25,000 fans are expected for  
Sunday's match, played at cozy Civic Stadium, the site where a 
frenzied crowd watch the U.S. men's team qualify for the World Cup 
two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The atmosphere's going to be somewhat similar to a World Cup  
game,'' said Milbrett, who with teammate Shannon MacMillan played 
at the University of Portland. ``It's going to be a rowdy crowd, 
it's going to be a pro-USA crowd. That's what we're going to count 
on in the World Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If there's any pressure on the team, it didn't show it Friday  
during the dedication of the Mia Hamm Building, a 
450,000-square-foot behemoth that dwarfs the Michael Jordan 
building on Nike's sprawling campus. Hamm seemed speechless, and 
although she actually shed tears when talking about her teammates, 
she kept the mood light, matching co-captain and team jokester 
Julie Foudy's wit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I promised Julie I'd name a (bathroom) stall after her,'' Hamm  
said. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
