<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Beaten Editor Says He Won't Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charges against two men accused of beating the  
former editor of the hip-hop magazine Blaze have been dropped 
because the journalist would not testify against them. 
</P>
<P>
	Deric ``D-Dot'' Angellettie and Anthony Hubbard, both 30, had  
been charged with assaulting Jesse Washington, 29, in his office 
last November. They could have gotten seven years in prison if 
convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge dismissed the charges last month at the request of  
prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne Brison, a spokesman for prosecutors, said Washington  
didn't explain why he wanted to abandon the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington did not immediately return a message left at his home  
on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Angellettie and Hubbard after Washington said  
they were two of four men who kicked him and threw chairs at him. 
Washington said he believed Angellettie was angry because Blaze 
identified him as the Madd Rapper, a performer who recorded songs 
anonymously. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington suffered fractured eye sockets that required hospital  
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Washington accused Fugees guitar player Wyclef Jean of  
pointing a gun at him in a recording studio because Jean didn't 
like Blaze's review of an album he had produced. Jean denied such 
an incident occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington, a former assistant bureau chief for The Associated  
Press in New York, was dismissed from Blaze in March in a dispute 
with his employers over editorial policies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
