<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Vice President Criticizes Coles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Pal Schmitt, an International Olympic  
Committee vice-president, said personal notes compiled by 
Australian IOC member Phil Coles ``are against the dignity, the 
pride'' of IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt told The Weekend Australian newspaper that there was  
``no doubt'' Coles was involved in writing material that broke 
``unwritten ethical rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was obvious Coles and partner Patricia Rosenbrock had  
written personal dossiers on the habits and tastes of IOC members 
``to help their friends in Salt Lake City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These personal notes are against the dignity, the pride of IOC  
members -- he should never have been involved,'' Schmitt said from 
Switzerland. ``This is not how an IOC member should behave. 
</P>
<P>
	``His personal relationships with IOC members will be frozen.''  
</P>
<P>
	The personal dossiers were uncovered in Salt Lake City last  
month after Coles had been warned by the IOC for accepting 
excessive hospitality from bid officials before and after they won 
the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles emerged confidently from a nearly three-hour hearing  
before an IOC investigating panel last week in Lausanne. The 
panel's recommendation will be forwarded to the IOC executive board 
at its June 14 meeting in Seoul, South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	A majority vote of the IOC general assembly, which will be held  
in Seoul following the board meeting, is required to expel an IOC 
member. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, a former Olympic rower for Australia who has been  
involved with the IOC for 17 years, has also been implicated in 
possible travel irregularities concerning the 1996 Atlanta bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Admitting to dispensing presents and favors in an effort to land  
the 1996 Games, Atlanta Olympic officials wrote a detailed internal 
report that was given to the U.S. House of Representatives Commerce 
Committee last week. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the report, Coles brought two travel companions on  
a trip to Atlanta in July 1989, which cost $13,053.21 and was paid 
for by the Atlanta group. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC rules limit members to one travel companion on such trips.  
</P>
<P>
	Coles said last week that he made one official visit to Atlanta  
-- in July 1989 -- and was accompanied by his wife and their young 
daughter. He said he was given dispensation to bring his child 
because she was classified as a minor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a normal visit,'' he said. ``It's absolutely above  
board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles said a second visit -- to tour Olympic sites -- was paid for  
by the Australian Olympic Committee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
