<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capital Offers Summer Entertainment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- From Shakespeare and Impressionist art to  
rock, Balkan folk music and the National Zoo, visitors to the 
nation's capital have their pick of free entertainment this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning Saturday, the Shakespeare Theatre will make free  
tickets available to all comers for a two-week performance of ``The 
Merry Wives of Windsor.'' Written as a farce, reportedly at the 
bidding of Queen Elizabeth I, the scene has been shifted from 
Windsor Castle to a 1950s New York mountain resort where the 
overweight John Falstaff tries his unsuccessful seductions in a 
sports jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	Performances are daily at the Carter Barron Amphitheater, which  
holds 4,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Every day at 6 p.m., the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts  
puts on an hourlong free show of popular, folk or classical music, 
in addition to its regular performances of films, plays, opera and 
concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	Entrance is always without charge to the Smithsonian's 15  
museums, which include the zoo and the Air and Space Museum. Many 
are open for extra evening hours through Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	So is the National Gallery of Art, which opens an exhibit Sunday  
of 55 works by Mary Cassatt, the only American artist among the 
French Impressionists. The gallery has a relaxing new sculpture 
garden next door, which matches the older outdoor sculpture park at 
the Hirschhorn Museum on the other side of the grassy National 
Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Gallery and some of the other museums have free  
films, but entry fees are charged for shows on the supersize Imax 
screens at the Natural History and the Air and Space museums. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, the Smithsonian presents all-day Folk Festivals on  
the Mall weekdays from June 23 to July 4. This year's event 
highlights the arts, crafts and cookery of three strikingly 
different places -- New Hampshire, Romania and South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be a special concert on June 24, which the  
Smithsonian promises will offer ``music and dance unlike anything 
most Americans have heard or seen before'' including wedding music 
from Bulgaria and Macedonia -- a blend of Balkan, Turkish and Indian 
music with jazz and rock. 
</P>
<P>
	A Conjunto Dance Party on July 2 presents music from south Texas  
that requires a diatonic button accordion and a 12-string bass 
guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Aug. 31 armed forces bands play daily on the east steps of  
the Capitol: Mondays, the Navy; Tuesdays and Fridays, the Air 
Force; Wednesdays, the Marines; and Thursdays, the Army. They also 
offer Sunday evening concerts on the Ellipse, just south of the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ellipse also is the site Wednesdays at 7 p.m. of a  
``Twilight Tattoo'' of the Army's Old Guard 3rd Infantry Band and 
Chorus. On Tuesdays at 8 p.m., the Navy Band and its specialty 
groups perform at the U.S. Navy Memorial, on Pennsylvania Avenue 
between the Capitol and the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	More information about what's going on can be obtained at the  
new Information Center in the Ronald Reagan Building on 
Pennsylvania Avenue, a block from the White House Visitor Center in 
the Commerce Department Building. 
</P>
<P>
	If visitors come to Washington for a taste of politics, Congress  
is in session until early August. Most committee meetings are open 
to the public. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
