<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrat Tapes GOP's Secret Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Democratic operative tape-recorded what was  
supposed to be a confidential meeting between Republican 
presidential hopeful Rep. John Kasich and drug-addicted women at 
their shelter, according to Kathy Sullivan, chairwoman of the New 
Hampshire Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the Odyssey Family Center in Canterbury, N.H.,  
complained to Sullivan, saying they invite all presidential 
candidates to speak on the condition of confidentiality. They asked 
the operative to turn over the tape during the meeting Tuesday but 
were refused, Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she then apologized to the shelter official and  
promised not to make public any part of the tape. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't enough for Kasich, however. In a letter Saturday to  
Democratic National Chairman Roy Romer, the Ohio congressman, 
chairman of the House Budget Committee complained about the episode 
and demanded an apology. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is nothing sacred anymore?'' Kasich wrote. ``Is there ever a  
time anymore when we can simply be Americans, instead of 
Republicans and Democrats looking for political advantage?'' He 
said the visit ``wasn't even a political event,'' although he 
talked about it at his next campaign stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the Odyssey Family Center nor the Democratic National  
Committee immediately responded to requests for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich campaign spokesman Todd Harris insisted it was a  
non-political visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``An event is public when it's been publicized, and political  
when the purpose of the event is to garner votes,'' he said. ``We 
did not invite the media, we did not ask for votes and we did not 
distribute campaign material.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic spokeswoman Sullivan said it's ironic that Kasich,  
who said he was worried about the confidentiality of the women on 
tape, has prompted media requests to hear it. Reporters are 
wondering whether Kasich said something he doesn't want anyone else 
to hear, she suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris said Kasich is concerned about outsiders hearing what the  
women said, not about anything he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``John did very little talking and quite a bit of listening,''  
Harris said, noting he's asking that the tape be returned to the 
center, not to Kasich. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan said she has not heard the tape, does not intend to  
listen to it and won't let anyone else hear it either. She plans to 
tape over that section. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich ``should be flattered, considering his standing in the  
polls, that someone actually followed him around that day,'' 
Sullivan said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
