<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A government troop pullback, ordered  
last year to spur peace talks with leftist rebels, has been 
extended until Dec. 7, the government's chief negotiator said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to keep troops out of rebel territory came less  
than two weeks after Defense Minister Rodrigo Lloreda resigned in 
protest at President Andres Pastrana's handling of efforts to end 
the 35-year-old civil conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Lloreda had objected most strenuously to the pronouncement by  
the chief negotiator, Victor G. Ricardo, that the pullout would be 
indefinite. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 2,000 troops were removed in November from a  
Switzerland-sized swath of southern Colombia to facilitate peace 
talks with the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. 
</P>
<P>
	Lloreda had warned that an indefinite troop withdrawal could  
lead to the permanent partitioning of Colombia into government and 
rebel-held areas -- a Balkanization of this already highly unstable 
nation where guerrillas control some 40 percent of the countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricardo also named the 20 members of a support committee  
designed to give advice to government and rebel negotiators. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A dispute among criminal gangs may  
have spurred nine gunmen to open fire on a crowded bar, killing six 
and wounding some 23 customers, police said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, it's our best hypothesis since two of the dead are  
known drug traffickers,'' Lt. Adilson Rodrigues of the 15th 
precinct told The Associated Press Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hooded gunmen fired assault rifles indiscriminately at more than  
100 customers Friday at the Friendly Bar in the Rio suburb city of 
Duque de Caxias. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident is one of Rio's most violent crimes since rogue  
police killed eight sleeping street kids and 21 slum dwellers in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Rio state Governor Anthony Garotinho, who recently signed a  
decree banning the sale of guns by authorized stores, has ordered a 
state wide manhunt. 
</P>
<P>
	Rio state Governor Anthony Garotinho, who recently signed a  
decree banning the sale of guns by authorized stores, has ordered a 
state wide manhunt. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The French consul in the southern Mexico city  
of Oaxaca and four other people were killed in a crash Saturday, 
the government news agency Notimex reported. The consul's wife was 
seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Killed in the crash were consul Manuel Gonzalez del Valle; the  
president of the Red Cross in Oaxaca, Alfredo Martinez Rodriguez; 
and a former city legislator, Luis Manuel de Jesus Castaneda 
Melgoza. The wives of Martinez Rodriguez and Castaneda Melgoza were 
also killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the six were in a sports utility vehicle that was  
apparently speeding on a highway in the central Mexican state of 
Puebla and crashed into a truck. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
