<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Revolution 2, Fire 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Joe-Max Moore and Ivan McKinley scored  
goals as the New England Revolution defeated the Chicago Fire 2-0 
Saturday night, their first regulation victory at home this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some quick counterattacks early in the match by Chicago,  
it was New England (5-6) that scored first when Moore converted in 
the 17th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	A tackle by McKinley stripped Peter Nowak of the ball about 10  
yards into the Chicago half of the field as Chicago was mounting a 
counterattack. McKinley, temporarily free of defenders, made a 
darting run down the left side before putting a cross into the Fire 
area that was volleyed home by Moore from seven yards. 
</P>
<P>
	McKinley headed in a cross by John Harkes in the 76th minute.  
</P>
<P>
	Chicago (6-5) had a handful of chances, but couldn't convert.  
</P>
<P>
	In the 36th minute, Fire forward Ante Razov got around New  
England's Brian Dunseth on the right side and broke in on the 
Revolution goal only to put a weak shot wide along the left post. 
</P>
<P>
	In the dying seconds of the first half, Chris Armas beat New  
England's offside trap as he broke in on the right side and hit an 
awkward shot from about 13 yards that deflected off Razov and went 
just wide of the left post. 
</P>
<P>
	The Revolution had not won in regulation since April 24 and had  
never beaten the defending MLS champions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
