<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Noteboook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) -- Maybe things are finally starting to go  
Jimmy Vasser's way. 
</P>
<P>
	After struggling through the first six races of the CART FedEx  
Series -- and watching rookie teammate Juan Montoya cruise to three 
victories and the series lead -- Vasser had a bemused smile Saturday 
after qualifying in the front row for the Miller Lite 225. 
</P>
<P>
	Finishing behind Helio Castro-Neves was Vasser's best qualifying  
effort of the season and the first front-row start for the 1996 
series champion since last year's finale in Fontana, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a lot of little things,'' Vasser said. ``We've had  
some failures and made some mistakes, just a lot of little crazy 
things. But we've been fortunate over time not to have those 
problems, so I'm not complaining. This is motor racing and these 
things happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thing is that there are still 14 races to go this  
season and we've got time to get it going. This could be what we 
needed to turn the corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another factor in Vasser's more optimistic outlook is that he  
got some guidance last week in a test session in Portland, Ore., 
from Morris Nunn, the engineer who helped former teammate Alex 
Zanardi -- now in Formula One -- win CART championships the past two 
years and has worked with Montoya this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Morris has got a deep well of knowledge and I hope we get to  
take advantage of it more this season,'' Vasser said. ``He really 
helped us turn in the right direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, Vasser's season hasn't been all that bad. He has  
finished in the points (among the top 12) in five of six races and 
is 11th in the standings, trailing Montoya by 48 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Each race has a total of 22 points, with one for the pole, one  
for leading the most laps and 20 for winning. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *POLE POSITION:* Last year, the Lola chassis was practically an  
orphan in the CART series. Now, with Castro-Neves and Hogan Racing 
helping to develop it, and Marlboro Team Penske putting Al Unser 
Jr. in a Lola, the British-built cars are having a renaissance of 
sorts. 
</P>
<P>
	The placing by Casto-Neves on Saturday was the first pole for  
Lola Cars international under the new ownership of Martin Birrane, 
who assumed control of the company in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	This is also the first pole for Lola since Andre Ribero was at  
the front for the street race in Toronto in 1996. The last oval 
pole for the company was by Scott Brayton at the 1995 Indianapolis 
500. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Andretti, who currently drives a Swift, was the last  
Lola driver to win a CART race, taking the checkered flag on the 
road course in Vancouver in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MICHAEL'S MILE:* Don't bet against Michael Andretti in Sunday's  
race at the Milwaukee Mile, even if he is starting a disappointing 
11th in the 26-car field. 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti, coming off a victory last weekend in Madison, Ill., is  
the leading active driver here with victories in 1986, 1987, 1991, 
1992 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	His Milwaukee resume also includes runner-up finishes in 1989  
and 1997, a third in 1995, fourths in 1984 and 1994 and fifth in 
1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love racing in Milwaukee and I love the fans,'' said  
Andretti, who leads all CART drivers with 38 victories. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MOVING AHEAD:* Rookie Cristiano da Matta qualified seventh for  
Sunday's race, giving a Toyota-powered car its second-highest 
starting spot since the company came into CART in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Da Matta, a 25-year-old Brazilian, set the standard for Toyota  
when he qualified sixth in his CART debut in Homestead, Fla. in 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 Indy Lights champion, now driving for Arciero-Wells  
Racing, will be making only his seventh start in the CART series. 
He also has registered Toyota's best finish (fourth) at the race 
last month in Nazareth, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Barron, a second-year driver, was 10th in a Toyota-powered  
car, giving Dan Gurney's All American Racers team its best start 
since the team returned to Champ car competition with Toyota in 
1996. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
