<DOCNO> APW19990605.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 19:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former AP Reporter Dies at 92 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINCHENDON, Mass. (AP) -- Maxwell Harrelson, a former  
correspondent for The Associated Press who covered the early years 
of World War II and the United Nations, has died. He was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrelson, who worked for the AP for more than four decades,  
died of a heart attack Friday at his home in Winchendon, relatives 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was an AP man until the day he died,'' said Harrelson's  
widow, Louise. ``He led a full, happy life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrelson was born in Warren, Ark., in 1906. He received his  
bachelor's degree from Ouachita Baptist University in Arkadelphia, 
Ark., and his master's from Northwestern University in Evanston, 
Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	As a reporter for the AP, Harrelson started in Albany, N.Y., and  
went on to serve as a correspondent in such countries as 
Yugoslavia, Greece and Hungary during the early years of World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	He later joined the war effort and served as a U.S. Army  
captain, Mrs. Harrelson said. 
</P>
<P>
	After his time overseas, Harrelson was chief AP correspondent at  
the United Nations for 22 years and won several awards for 
outstanding reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was a part-time faculty member at Columbia University's  
Graduate School of Journalism. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrelson retired in 1972 and moved to Winchendon.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his wife, Harrelson is survived by two children,  
three grandchildren, three brothers and a sister. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial service and burial are scheduled for Friday morning  
at the Immaculate Heart of Mary Church in Winchendon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
