<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Ends Inquiry of HUD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A court this week quietly ended the nine-year  
investigation of influence-peddling in the Department of Housing 
and Urban Development, the longest inquiry under the independent 
counsel law. 
</P>
<P>
	Three federal appeals judges issued a two-page ``order of  
termination'' in the $29 million investigation and transferred the 
only remaining case, involving former top HUD aide Deborah Gore 
Dean, to the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The court order was stamped Thursday and released Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Dean was convicted of conspiracy to defraud, receiving an  
illegal gratuity, perjury and concealing and covering up material 
facts from investigators. She has filed motions seeing a new trial. 
</P>
<P>
	She blamed former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce and other  
department officials in the Reagan administration for deciding to 
funnel housing projects to developers who hired consultants such as 
former Kentucky Gov. Louis Nunn. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce was never charged, but he admitted in a statement to the  
prosecutor's office that his conduct ``contributed to an 
environment'' in which HUD staff members engaged in ``improper and 
even criminal conduct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The special appeals court launched the HUD investigation in  
March 1990 by appointing Independent Counsel Arlin Adams. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation yielded 17 convictions and more than $2  
million in fines and recovered $10 million in federal low-income 
housing funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those convicted was former Interior Secretary James Watt,  
who pleaded guilty to withholding information and documents from a 
grand jury. Prosecutors gathered evidence that Watt had been paid 
more than $500,000 for contacting political appointees at HUD from 
1984 through 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent counsel statute expires June 30 and appears  
unlikely to be renewed, at least not immediately. Congressional 
Democrats claim that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's 
investigation of the Clinton administration has been out of 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans made a similar charge regarding Independent Counsel  
Lawrence Walsh and his pursuit of GOP officials in the Iran-Contra 
matter. President Bush closed out Walsh's probe by pardoning former 
Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger two weeks before he was to have 
gone on trial in the scandal -- a case in which Bush's own actions 
were to come under scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh's was the most expensive independent counsel  
investigation: $48.5 million for a six-year inquiry regarding the 
Reagan White House's arms-for-hostages deals with Iran and its 
secret war against the communist-led government of Nicaragua. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's nearly five-year criminal investigation of President  
Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton has cost some $40 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990605.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 20:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Can Only Watch This Big Shot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Though it wasn't eight points in 8.9 seconds, it  
was the type of finish that left Reggie Miller in awe. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, the king of the improbable, seemingly unmakeable shot in  
this Knicks-Pacers rivalry, was an innocent bystander when Larry 
Johnson pulled off the kind of dramatic play Miller has perfected 
for the better part of this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm usually on the other end of a shot like that,'' Miller  
said Saturday night after Johnson's four-point play with 5.7 
seconds left gave the Knicks a 92-91 victory in Game 3 of the 
Eastern Conference finals. ``When he makes a shot like that, it 
makes it tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller could only stand there and gaze blankly, his tongue  
hanging out the way Spike Lee and so many New Yorkers have stared 
at him. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller is the expert on late comebacks steeped in drama,  
especially in Madison Square Garden. But in the fourth quarter of 
this pivotal game, Miller didn't score, and in the second half, he 
had just two points on 1-for-4 shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Miller, who won Game 2 of this series with two free throws  
with 2 seconds left, had to watch Johnson hit a shot that rivaled 
even some of his most crushing blows against the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I've seen a lot of things,'' Miller said. ``It was  
surprising to me. Always when you have a three-point lead, you say 
to yourself, the worst you could do is tie. But that old adage 
proved us wrong tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For years in New York, the adage has been simple: Keep Reggie  
away from the Garden in the summertime. If that doesn't work, keep 
the ball away from him when he arrives. 
</P>
<P>
	So many times during the second half, as the Pacers tried to  
hold on to their dwindling lead, Miller was on the court but was 
barely noticed. 
</P>
<P>
	Even on the Pacers' last possession, Miller never saw the ball.  
When Mark Jackson missed a running 10-footer in the lane, few were 
as surprised as the Knicks defenders that the fingertips launching 
the ball didn't belong to Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought the ball was going to go to Reggie,'' Knicks guard  
Chris Childs said. ``It looked like nobody wanted it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What a strange sight it was for Miller, whose eight incredible  
points in 8.9 seconds killed the Knicks in Game 4 of the 1994 
Eastern Conference finals, to be left standing with his mouth 
hanging open after Johnson's shot. Even during the Pacers' final 
timeout, he appeared to be barely paying attention -- still staring 
into space, toward Eighth Avenue, and then up at the scoreboard. 
</P>
<P>
	It read Knicks 92, Pacers 91. Miller and his teammates had a  
hard time figuring out why. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reggie really doesn't need to score 30 points for us to win  
every night,'' Pacers coach Larry Bird said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doesn't he have to score in the fourth quarter, though?  
</P>
<P>
	It was Miller, after all, who hung 25 on the Knicks in the  
fourth quarter of Game 5 of the Eastern Conference finals at the 
Garden in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little disappointing,'' Miller said. ``I felt that Mark  
did get off a pretty good shot in the paint. You want to give 
yourself a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel my moment will come.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
