<DOCNO> APW19990605.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-05 21:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Men Win Track Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- It would have been appropriate for Arkansas'  
men's track and field athletes to throw coach John McDonnell into 
the steeplechase water jump pit Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, it was steeplechaser Matt Kerr's victory that helped  
propel the Razorbacks to their eight consecutive title at the NCAA 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Of all the wins, this was one of the closest. Arkansas finished  
with 59 points, only seven ahead of Stanford. The teams also 
finished 1-2 last year, with Arkansas winning by 7 1/2 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's title race also was a repeat of last year, as Texas  
again won the championship with 62 points and UCLA was second with 
60. The difference last year was five points. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's race was even more dramatic than the men's. Heading  
into the final event, UCLA led with 54 points, Texas was second 
with 52 and Southern California third with 50. 
</P>
<P>
	Suziann Reid, who earlier Saturday became the meet's first  
three-time winner in the women's 400 meters, ran a powerful anchor 
in the 1,600 relay, leading the Longhorns to victory in 3 minutes, 
27.08 seconds. The time was a collegiate record, breaking the mark 
of 3:27.50 set by Texas in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern California anchor Kinshasha Davis passed UCLA's  
Michelle Perry down the final straightaway and finished second, 
preventing the arch-rival Bruins from tying Texas for the title. 
The Trojans finished third with 58 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerr, a senior competing for the final time for Arkansas, made  
the 3,000 steeplechase a memorable race. He bided his time before 
taking the lead from UTEP's Carlos Suarez-Gonzales with two laps 
remaining and coasted home by about 14 meters in 8:44.29. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas also picked up points in the 1,500 as two-time  
defending champion Seneca Lassiter finished second and Sharif Karie 
was fifth, in the triple jump as long jump champion Melvin Lister 
took fifth, in the high jump as 1998 indoor champion Kenny Evans 
placed third and in the shot put as Marcus Clavelle was fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	That enabled the Razorbacks to overcome Stanford's 22-point lead  
going into the final day. On Saturday, the Cardinal got only a 
fourth from Adam Connolly in the hammer throw and a seventh in the 
1,500 from Jake Maas. 
</P>
<P>
	The most scintillating individual performance of the competition  
was Florida freshman John Capel's 19.87 victory in the 200 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Capel tied the meet record set by Mississippi State's Lorenzo  
Daniel in 1988 and tied for fourth place among all-time collegiate 
runners. Only Joe DeLoach, Ato Boldon and Michael Johnson have run 
faster. 
</P>
<P>
	``If me and Coby (Miller of Auburn) came off the turn together,  
I knew it would be just like the SEC,'' Capel said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's just what happened.  
</P>
<P>
	Capel and Miller were running side by side as they entered the  
final straightaway. Just like in the Southeastern Conference 
championships, Capel had the better kick. Miller wound up second in 
a career-best 20.04. 
</P>
<P>
	UCLA's Seilala Sua set a meet record in winning her third  
consecutive women's discus title at 210-10, bettering by two inches 
the mark she set last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory also gave Sua a shot put-discus double, the fourth  
in the meet's history and the first since UCLA's Tracie Millett did 
it in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	There were several other sparkling performances.  
</P>
<P>
	Leonard Myles-Mills didn't pay any attention to the more  
heralded runners in the men's 100 -- and made his own kind of 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	The BYU senior raced to victory in 9.98, making him the first  
repeat champion in the event since Auburn's Harvey Glance in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Glance, now the coach at Alabama, was on hand to present the  
first-place medal to Myles-Mills. 
</P>
<P>
	The winning time was a record at Boise State's Bronco Stadium  
and tied Myles-Mills for eighth place on the all-time collegiate 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into the race, all of the attention was focused on Miller  
and Capel. Neither came close to Myles-Mills as Capel was second in 
10.03 and Miller sixth in 10.21. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid got the Texas women started on their way to repeating by  
winning the 400 in 51.09, a stadium record. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were depending on me to get 10 points,'' Reid said.  
</P>
<P>
	There was a surprise in the women's 100, as Southern Cal  
freshman Angela Williams, the 1998 High School Athlete of the Year, 
beat two-time defending champion Debbie Ferguson of Georgia. 
Williams bolted into the lead at the start and finished in 11.04. 
Ferguson was second in 11.10. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the greatest day of my life,'' Williams said. ``It's  
like the Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the easiest victory in one of the short races was turned  
in by South Carolina's Terrence Trammell. He won the men's 110 
hurdles in 13.45, a stadium record, and two meters ahead of 
runner-up Dawane Wallace of Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	In a blanket finish, Miami's Yolanda McCray won the women's 100  
hurdles in 12.85 with Georgia Tech's Andria King second in 12.87 
and UCLA's Joanna Hayes third in 12.89. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball State's Latasha Jenkins took the women's 200 in 22.29, a  
stadium record, as Ferguson, again the defending champion, finished 
second in 22.53. 
</P>
<P>
	Other notable performances were Mark Boswell of Texas in the  
men's high jump at 7-7 3/4, LeVar Anderson of LSU in the men's triple 
jump with a wind-aided 56-2, and UCLA's 3:02.12 in the men's 1,600 
relay. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the biggest surprises was Clyde Colenzo's victory in the  
men's 1,500. The SMU senior outdueled Lassiter to win the tactical 
race in 3:47.54. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
