<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Charged in Tour Bus Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRUCKEE, Calif. (AP) -- The driver involved in a Sierra tour bus  
crash last year that killed two passengers and injured nearly three 
dozen others has been charged with misdemeanor manslaughter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nevada County District Attorney's Office filed the charges  
against William Collier, 53, of Clearlake Oaks, Calif., in the 
Interstate 80 crash near Farad, 15 miles east of Truckee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sept. 26 accident resulted in the deaths of a 59-year-old  
Vallejo woman and a 44-year-old Berkeley man. Thirty-five other 
passengers were injured, five of them critically. 
</P>
<P>
	The criminal complaint alleges Collier was driving a Coach USA  
bus from San Francisco to a Reno, Nev., casino when he lost control 
on a curve and allowed it to overturn. 
</P>
<P>
	A California Highway Patrol investigation concluded the bus  
drifted off the roadway after Collier spent too much time looking 
into the rear view mirror. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, he made a driving error when he was changing  
lanes,'' said CHP Sgt. Hal Koehncke. 
</P>
<P>
	``The misdemeanor arises from the fact it wasn't a grievous  
error like drunken driving or reckless driving,'' Koehncke said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
